#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _focus peaking_ module allows you to identify which parts of the image are sharp and in-focus. It works both in the lighttable view, where you can easily see at a glance which images are sharp and which are blurry, and in the darkroom view, when you are processing a single image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The module is activated by clicking on the focus-peaking icon (![focus-peaking-icon](./focus-peaking/focus-peaking-icon.png#icon)). It highlights the sharp parts of the image with a yellow, green and blue overlay:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![focus-peaking-overview](./focus-peaking/focus-peaking-overview.png#w75)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The module works by filtering out image noise, measuring the gradients of intensity in the image and calculating average and standard deviation statistics. When the gradient of an edge differs significantly from the mean, the associated pixels are marked up with a \"heat map\" indicating how sharp the edge is.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_yellow_ represents a large (6σ) jump in gradient, indicating a very sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_green_ represents a medium (4σ) jump in gradient, indicating a reasonably sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_blue_ represents a small (2σ) jump in gradient, indicating a slightly sharp edge.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/focus-peaking.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The image above was taken with a wide aperture to give a shallow depth of field, and you can see how the camera has focused on the chinese character written on the second red lantern along from the front. There are also stems of the pink flowers which fall within the area of acceptable sharpness around the focal plane, and these have also been marked up with yellow and green.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "geotagging"
msgstr "геотегування"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Import and apply GPX track data to a selection of images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is common to the [lighttable](../../../lighttable/_index.md) and [map](../../../map/_index.md) views. However, an enhanced mode is provided in the map view that allows you to preview the position of the images along the GPS tracks while adjusting the images' date/time (offset) and time zone.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "workflow overview"
msgstr "огляд робочого процесу"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A GPS receiver calculates its current position based on the information it receives from satellites and records it in a GPX file, together with the current date and time. The Exif data of the images also contains a time stamp defined by the camera settings. The _geotagging_ module takes the time stamp of the image, looks up the position in the GPX file at that time, and stores the appropriate coordinates (latitude/longitude/elevation) in its database and the image's XMP sidecar file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Two problems may occur during this process:\n"
"- In contrast to GPS devices, most cameras don't record the time accurately.\n"
"- The time stored in the Exif data does not include the time zone. Most people set their camera to local time, while the GPS devices store the time in the UTC (Universal Time, Coordinated, i.e. Greenwich (London)) time zone. If the time zones of camera and GPX file differs, than the related location will be wrong.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If your image already shows the correct date/time and carries the UTC time stamp, you can directly apply the GPX track file without further adjustments.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Otherwise follow the following process to correlate the time of the camera and GPS tracker\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Fix the camera time setting for an individual image by manually entering the correct date/time for that image into the _date/time_ field. A good way is to do this is to take a photograph of a reliable time source. This can be any precise clock or, even better, the time displayed on your GPS device, bearing in mind that GPS devices normally _show_ the local time, even though they _store_ universal time. The difference (offset) between the time entered and the time stored in the image's Exif data will be shown in the _date/time offset_ field.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Press the _lock_ button to lock the calculated offset.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select all of the images you wish to adjust and apply the calculated offset to those images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If the camera time zone is not UTC, set the time zone in the _camera time zone_ field.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "With the time setting corrected, you can now apply GPX tracking data using the _apply GPX track file_ button.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "module controls (common)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"date/time\n"
": This field is initialized with the date/time read from the first selected image (format `yyyy:mm:dd hh:mm:ss`) and can be modified to correct the date/time for that image. The individual date/time fields can be altered by scrolling over them with your mouse. If any field reaches its limit, the neighboring fields are automatically updated. For example, if you go over 60 on the minute field, the hour field will automatically be incremented.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"original date/time\n"
": The original date/time of the image is shown here for reference.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"date/time offset\n"
": The calculated difference between the original date/time that keyed in the _date/time_ field. If the calculated difference is greater than plus or minus 99 days 23 hours 59 minutes and 59 seconds, the offset is invalidated.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lock button\n"
": If the lock button is activated, the offset value is frozen. If you subsequently change the selected image(s), the new image date/time is updated using the locked offset. This allows you to apply the same offset to different images selections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/shared/geotagging.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"apply offset button\n"
": Apply the offset on selected images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
