#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "snapshots"
msgstr "миттєві знімки"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A snapshot is a stored bitmap of the center image in the darktable view. Snapshots can be taken at any point in the development process and later selected to be overlaid onto the current center view. This allows you to undertake a side by side comparison (by default left=snapshot, right=active edit) while you are tuning parameters of a module. This can also be combined with [history stack](./history-stack.md) module to compare a snapshot against different stages of development. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To take a snapshot, click on the _take snapshot_ button in the snapshot module. Above the button you will see a list of the various snapshots that have been taken for this editing session. The name of each snapshot reflects the most recent module name and history stack position that was active at the time the snapshot was taken.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the name of a snapshot to enable a split view between the saved snapshot image and the current state of the processed image. You can control the split view by moving the splitline back and forth over the image with your mouse. If you hover with the mouse over the splitline, a small rotation icon will appear on the center of the line. Click this icon to change between vertical and horizontal split view. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At all times, an arrow containing the letter \"S\" is displayed to indicate which side of the image is the snapshot and which is the current edit.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the module's reset button to remove all existing snapshots.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/snapshots.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Snapshots are retained for the duration of your darktable session. This means that you can also use snapshots to compare with a duplicate edit of the same image. Just navigate to that image and enable the snapshot view as normal.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color assessment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When developing an image, the way we perceive brightness, contrast and saturation is influenced by the surrounding ambient conditions. If an image is displayed against a dark background, as with the default theme in darktable, it can have the a number of adverse effects on our perception of that image:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Exaggeration of the perceived exposure makes the image seems brighter than it really is. This is nicely illustrated by the [Adelson checkerboard shadow effect](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Checker_shadow_illusion).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A decrease in the perceived saturation in the image makes the colors seem less rich than they really are (the Hunt effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A decrease in the perceived contrast in the image makes the tones seem flatter than they really are (Bartleson-Breneman effect 3)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The end result is that the image can end up being too dark, and overly-processed in terms of contrast and color saturation. To avoid this, the \"ISO 12646:2008\" standard makes some recommendations about the conditions under which the colors of an image should be assessed. The _color assessment_ module in the darkroom places a frame around the image to help the user better assess the colors in the image, along the lines of those recommendations.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![color-assessment-overview](./color-assessment/color-assessment-overview.png#w75)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the lightbulb icon (![bulb-icon](./color-assessment/bulb-icon.png#icon)) is selected in the bottom panel, the image is zoomed out so that a thick mid-gray border appears around the image to act as a reference against which to compare the image's tones. A thinner white border is placed immediately around the image to give the eyes a basis for comparison when looking at parts of the image that are meant to be a bright white.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Although the color assessment mode provides a mid-gray surrounding to the image, it is recommended that you also set your user interface (in [preferences > general](../../../preferences-settings/general.md)) to one of the \"gray\" themes. These themes are designed to provide a user interface that is close to middle gray (it is actually slightly darker to allow better contrast with the text in the user interface). When one of these themes is used together with the color assessment mode, this will help to avoid the above perception issues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/color-assessment.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Color assessment mode can also be toggled by pressing Ctrl+B.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "raw overexposed warning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This option warns you about areas of your raw input image with clipped color channels. Clipped color channels imply an overexposed image with loss of information in the affected areas. You may use the [_highlight reconstruction_](../../processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md) or [_color reconstruction_](../../processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md) modules to attempt to reconstruct these areas.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on the icon to open a dialog containing the following configuration parameters. \t\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Choose how to mark clipped areas:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - _mark with CFA color_: Display a pattern of the respective primary colors (red, green, and blue) to indicate which color channels are clipped. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - _mark with solid color_: Mark clipped areas with a user defined solid color (see below) independent of the affected color channels. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - _false color_: Set clipped color channels to zero in the affected areas.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color scheme\n"
": Choose the solid color for the _mark with solid color_ mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/raw-overexposed.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping threshold\n"
": Set the threshold defining what values are considered to be overexposed. You can safely leave this slider at its default value of 1.0 (white level) in most cases. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Query and modify the [history stack](../../../darkroom/pixelpipe/history-stack.md) of the current darkroom image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module lists every change of state (activate/de-activate/move/change parameters) for all processing modules that have been modified for the current image. You can select a point in the stack to return to that point in the development history of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Caution:** adjusting any module will cause all modules above the currently selected one to be discarded. It is easy to lose development work on an image in this way!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It is safe to quit the program, leave the darkroom mode, or switch to another image while having selected some earlier state in the history stack module. When returning to that image you will find the history stack panel in the state where you left it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Hovering the mouse over an item in the history stack will show a tooltip with details of all changes that were made in that module compared to its previous or default state. This can help track down adjustments that were made unintentionally and have unintended effects.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Clicking “compress history stack” generates the shortest history stack that reproduces the current image. It causes all edits above the currently-selected step to be discarded. If any module appears multiple times in the remainder of the stack, these multiple appearances will be _compressed_ into a single step in the history.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Clicking \"compress history stack\" while holding the Ctrl key truncates the history stack, but without compressing it i.e. it discards all modules above the currently selected one but leaves the remainder of the history stack unchanged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Clicking the \"reset parameters\" button in the module header discards the entire history stack and reactivates any default modules. This can also be achieved by selecting the \"original image\" history item and clicking \"compress history stack\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The button to the right of the \"compress history stack\" button allows you to create a new style from the history stack of the current image, which can then be applied to other images. Use the first line of the popup dialog window to name your style and the second to add a searchable description. You will be prompted to choose which of the current history stack modules to include in the style.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/history-stack.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once created, styles can be managed and applied to other images with the lighttable's [styles](../lighttable/styles.md) module.  You can also assign shortcut keys to your styles (see [preferences > shortcuts](../../../preferences-settings/shortcuts.md)) and apply the associated style to all selected images by pressing the shortcut key whenever you are in the lighttable or darkroom view.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "soft proof"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the icon on the right of the bottom panel to activate the soft proof display mode on your image. Soft proof allows you to preview your image rendered using a printer profile to see how colors will end up on the final print. You can also activate soft proof with the keyboard shortcut Ctrl+S. A message “soft proof\" on the bottom left of your image tells you that you are in soft proof display mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on the icon to open a dialog with the following configuration parameters. For each of these parameters, the list of available profiles is read from `$DARKTABLE/share/darktable/color/out` and `$HOME/.config/darktable/color/out` (where `$DARKTABLE` represents darktable's installation directory and `$HOME` your home directory).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"display profile\n"
": Set the color profile for the display. The option “system display profile” is the preferred setting when working with a calibrated display. The profile is taken either from your system's color manager or from your X display server. The method darktable uses to detect your system display profile can be changed in [preferences > miscellaneous](../../../preferences-settings/miscellaneous.md). For more information see [display profile](../../../special-topics/color-management/display-profile.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"preview display profile\n"
": Set the color profile for the preview image if you are using a second window.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"intent\n"
": Set the rendering intent for your display -- only available if rendering with LittleCMS2 is activated. See [rendering intent](../../../special-topics/color-management/rendering-intent.md) for a list of available options. This option appears twice -- once for the \"display profile\" and once for the \"preview display profile\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"softproof profile\n"
": Set the color profile for soft proofing. Typically these profiles are supplied by your printer or generated during printer profiling.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/soft-proof.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"histogram profile\n"
": Set the color profile of the histogram.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "mask manager"
msgstr "менеджер масок"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Manage all masks and shapes for the current image. \n"
msgstr "Керує всіма масками та фігурами для поточного зображення. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![mask manager](./mask-manager/mask-manager.png#w25)\n"
msgstr "![менеджер масок](./mask-manager/mask-manager.png#w25)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module can be used to create, rename, edit and delete shapes. You can add shapes to and remove shapes from a mask, group shapes together, and combine them using set operators. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In the top line of the mask manager panel are buttons that can be used to create new shapes. These are the same as in the [drawn mask](../../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) interface of the individual modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The panel below these buttons displays a list of all masks and individual shapes defined for the current image. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Groups of shapes forming a mask are displayed with a headline in the form \"grp <module_name>\" indicating the module in which they are used, with the component shapes listed below. The list of mask groups is followed by a list of all individual shapes that have been generated in the context of the current image. If a shape is in use by any masks this is indicated by a symbol to the right of the shape name. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "shapes"
msgstr "фігури"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default each shape receives an automatically generated name, consisting of the shape type (\"brush\", \"circle\", \"ellipse\", \"path\", \"gradient\") and an automatically-incremented integer. You can rename a shape by double-clicking on its current name. It is a good habit to give shapes and groups meaninful names, especially if you are going to use the same selection in different masks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on a shape name to show the selected shape on the image canvas with all of its controls, allowing you to edit the properties of just that shape. This is especially useful where there are many overlapping shapes within a mask, making it difficult to select the right one with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Right-click on a shape name to show a menu with options to remove the current shape or to remove all shapes not currently in use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** darktable retains all shapes that have ever been defined for the current image unless you explicitly remove them. If you choose to include develop history when exporting an image, all defined shapes will be exported with the image. Beware that if the list of shapes is very long the space required to store those shapes might exceed the size limit of certain file formats. This can cause XMP tag creation to fail during export.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/utility-modules/darkroom/mask-manager.md
#: content/darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "masks"
msgstr "маски"

#. type: Plain text
