#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "exposure"
msgstr "експозиція"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Increase or decrease the overall brightness of an image. \n"
msgstr "Збільшує або зменшує загальну яскравість зображення. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module has two modes of operation:\n"
msgstr "Цей модуль має два режими роботи:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"manual\n"
": Set the _exposure_, _black level_ and _clipping threshold_ manually\n"
msgstr ""
"вручну\n"
": Встановити _експозицію_, _рівень чорного_ та _поріг кліппінгу_ вручну\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"automatic (RAW images only)\n"
": Use an analysis of the image's histogram to automatically set the exposure. Darktable automatically selects the exposure compensation that is required to shift the selected _percentile_ to the selected _target level_ (see definitions below). This mode is particularly useful for automatically altering a large number of images to have the same exposure. A typical use case of automatic mode is deflickering of time-lapse photographs. \n"
msgstr ""
"автоматично (лише RAW-зображення)\n"
": Використовує аналіз гістограми зображення, щоб автоматично встановити "
"експозицію. darktable автоматично вибирає компенсацію експозиції, необхідну "
"для зміщення вибраного _процентилю_ на вибраний _цільовий рівень_ (див. "
"визначення нижче). Цей режим особливо корисний для автоматичного "
"встановлення однакової експозиції великій кількості зображень. Типовим "
"варіантом використання автоматичного режиму є дефлікеринг знімків таймлапс "
"фотографії. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": Choose the mode of operation (automatic/manual)\n"
msgstr ""
"режим\n"
": Вибирає режим роботи (автоматичний/вручну)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compensate camera exposure (manual mode)\n"
": Automatically remove the camera exposure bias (taken from the image's Exif data)\n"
msgstr ""
"компенсувати експозицію камери (ручний режим)\n"
": Автоматичне видалення зміщення експозиції камери (взятого з даних Exif "
"зображення)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"exposure (manual mode)\n"
": Increase (move to the right) or decrease (move to the left) the exposure value (EV)\n"
msgstr ""
"експозиція (ручний режим)\n"
": Збільшує (переміщення вправо) або зменшує (переміщення вліво) значення "
"експозиції (EV)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping threshold (manual mode)\n"
": Define what percentage of bright values are to be clipped in the calculation of the _exposure_ and _black level correction_. Use the color picker to sample a portion of the image to be used for this calcuation.\n"
msgstr ""
"поріг кліппінгу (ручний режим)\n"
": Визначає, який процент яскравих значень слід відсікати при обчисленні "
"_експозиції_ та _корекції рівня чорного_. Використовуйте піпетку кольорів "
"для вибірки частини зображення, яка буде використана для цього обчислення.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"percentile (automatic mode)\n"
": Define a location in the histogram to use for automatic exposure correction. A percentile of 50% denotes a position in the histogram where 50% of pixel values are above and 50% of pixel values are below that exposure.\n"
msgstr ""
"процентиль (автоматичний режим)\n"
": Визначає місце в гістограмі, яке використовуватиметься для автоматичної "
"корекції експозиції. 50% процентиля позначає позицію в гістограмі, де 50% "
"значень пікселів вище, а 50% значень пікселів нижче цієї експозиції.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"target level (automatic mode)\n"
": Define the target level for automatic exposure correction (EV) relative to the white point of the camera.\n"
msgstr ""
"цільовий рівень (автоматичний режим)\n"
": Визначає цільовий рівень для автоматичної корекції експозиції (EV) щодо "
"точки білого камери.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"black level correction (manual and automatic modes)\n"
": Adjust the black level point to unclip negative RGB values. \n"
msgstr ""
"корекція рівня чорного (ручний та автоматичний режими)\n"
": Регулює точку рівня чорного, щоб зняти негативні значення RGB. \n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Do not use the black level correction to add more density in blacks as this can clip near-black colors out of gamut by generating negative RGB values. This can cause problems with some modules later in the pixelpipe. Instead, use a tone mapping curve to add density to the blacks (e.g. use the _relative black exposure_ slider on the _scene_ tab of [filmic rgb](filmic-rgb.md), or establish a deeper toe in [base curve](base-curve.md)).\n"
msgstr ""
"**Примітка:** Не використовуйте корекцію рівня чорного, щоб додати більшу "
"щільність найтемнішим тонам, оскільки це може відсікати майже чорні кольори "
"з охоплення, створюючи негативні значення RGB. Це може спричинити проблеми з "
"деякими модулями пізніше в конвеєрі обробки. Натомість використовуйте криву "
"тонового відображення, щоб додати щільності найтемнішим тонам (наприклад, "
"використовуйте повзунок _ експозиція відносно чорного_ на вкладці _вхід_ у ["
"filmic rgb](filmic-rgb.md), або опустіть нижню частину в [базовій кривій"
"](base-curve.md)).\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "rgb curve"
msgstr "крива rgb"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/tone-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A classic digital photography tool to alter an image's tones using curves.\n"
msgstr ""
"Класичний інструмент цифрової фотографії для зміни тонів зображення за "
"допомогою кривих.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is very similar to the [_tone curve_](./tone-curve.md) module but works in RGB color space.\n"
msgstr ""
"Цей модуль дуже схожий на модуль [_тонова крива_](./tone-curve.md), але "
"працює в кольоровому просторі RGB.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Activate the color picker on the left to show the picked values in the graph (Ctrl+click to use the picker in area mode). Numerical (Lab) values of the input and output (see below) at the selected spot or area are shown at the top left of the widget.\n"
msgstr ""
"Активуйте піпетку кольорів ліворуч, щоб відобразити вибрані значення на "
"графіку (Ctrl+клік, щоб використовувати піпетку в режимі області). Числові "
"(Lab) значення входу та виходу (див. нижче) у вибраній точці або області "
"відображаються у верхньому лівому куті віджета.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A second color picker to the right can be used to automtaically create new nodes based on the sampled area. Ctrl+click+drag to alter the created nodes to have a positive curve for the selected area; Shift+click+drag to create a negative curve.\n"
msgstr ""
"Друга піпетка кольору праворуч може бути використана для автоматичного "
"створення нових вузлів на основі області вибірки. Ctrl+клік +перетягування – "
"змінити створені вузли, щоб мати позитивну криву для вибраної області; "
"Shift+клік+перетягування –створити негативну криву.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Please refer to the [curves](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md) section for more details about how to modify curves including the **interpolation method** and **preserve colors** controls._\n"
msgstr ""
"_Зверніться до розділу [криві](../../darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md), "
"щоб отримати докладнішу інформацію про те, як модифікувати криві, включаючи "
"елементи керування **метод інтерполяції** та **збереження кольорів**._\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mode\n"
": RGB is a linear color space designed to capture and display images in additive synthesis. It is related to the capture and display media and does not isolate color and lightness information in the same way that Lab and XYZ color spaces do. This module works in ProPhoto RGB. Adding contrast in RGB space is known to desaturate highlights and boost saturation in the shadows, but this has been proven to be the most reliable way to edit contrast, and is the standard method in most software\n"
msgstr ""
"режим\n"
": RGB - це лінійний кольоровий простір, призначений для захоплення та "
"відображення зображень в адитивному синтезі. Він пов’язаний із засобами "
"знімання та відображення та не ізолює інформацію про колір та яскравість так "
"само, як це роблять кольорові простори Lab і XYZ. Цей модуль працює в "
"ProPhoto RGB. Відомо, що додавання контрасту в просторі RGB зменшує "
"насиченість у світлих тонах та посилює насиченість у тінях, але було "
"доведено, що це найбільш надійний спосіб редагування контрасту, до того ж "
"він є стандартним методом у більшості програмного забезпечення\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Depending on the desired intent you can apply the RGB curve in two different modes\n"
msgstr ""
": Залежно від бажаного наміру ви можете застосувати криву RGB у двох різних "
"режимах\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _RGB, linked channels_: Apply the L-channel curve to all three channels in the RGB color space.\n"
": - _RGB, independent channels_: R, G and B curves can be adjusted independently.\n"
msgstr ""
": - _RGB, пов'язані канали_: Застосувати криву L-каналу до всіх трьох "
"каналів у колірному просторі RGB.\n"
": - _RGB, незалежні канали_: Криві R, G і B можна регулювати незалежно.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compensate middle gray\n"
": Select this to change the histogram display in the module. This option does not alter the processing but may assist when editing the curve.\n"
msgstr ""
"компенсація середньо-сірого\n"
": Виберіть це, щоб змінити відображення гістограми в модулі. Ця опція не "
"змінює обробку, але може допомогти при редагуванні кривої.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color reconstruction"
msgstr "відновлення кольору"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Recover color information in blown-out highlights.\n"
msgstr "Відновлює інформацію про колір у переекспонованих ділянках.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Due to the nature of digital sensors, overexposed highlights lack valid color information. Most frequently they appear neutral white or exhibit some color cast -- depending on what other image processing steps are involved. This module can “heal” overexposed highlights by replacing their colors with better fitting ones. The module acts on pixels whose luminance exceeds a user-defined threshold. Replacement colors are taken from neighboring pixels. Both the spatial distance and the luminance distance (range) are taken into account for color selection.\n"
msgstr ""
"Через природу цифрових сенсорів у надмірно освітлених ділянках відсутня "
"достовірна інформація про колір. Найчастіше вони виглядають нейтрально "
"білими або демонструють певне підфарбування -- залежно від того, які інші "
"етапи обробки зображень задіяні. Цей модуль може “вилікувати” "
"переекспоновані ділянки, замінивши їх кольори на більш підходящі. Модуль діє "
"на пікселі, яскравість яких перевищує визначений користувачем поріг. Кольори "
"заміни беруться із сусідніх пікселів. При виборі кольору враховуються як "
"просторова відстань, так і відстань освітленості (діапазон).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Due to a limitation of the underlying algorithm, reconstructed colors may sometimes be displayed incorrectly if you zoom into the image in the darkroom view. If this happens you might observe a magenta shift in highlight areas close to high contrast edges, or you might see colorless highlight areas when used alongside the “reconstruct color” method of the [_highlight reconstruction_](./highlight-reconstruction.md) module. These artifacts only influence on-screen image display – the final output remains unaffected. It is recommended that you finetune the parameters of this module only when viewing the fully zoomed-out image.\n"
msgstr ""
"Через обмеження базового алгоритму реконструйовані кольори іноді можуть "
"відображатися неправильно, якщо збільшити зображення в режимі темної "
"кімнати. Якщо це трапиться, ви можете спостерігати зміщення в мадженту в "
"найсвітліших областях, близьких до контурів із високою контрастністю, або ви "
"можете побачити безбарвні області, коли одночасно використовується метод “"
"відновлення кольору” модуля [_відновлення переекспонованих ділянок_"
"](./highlight-reconstruction.md). Ці артефакти впливають лише на "
"відображення зображення на екрані – остаточний результат залишається "
"незмінним. Рекомендується тонко регулювати параметри цього модуля лише під "
"час перегляду повністю зменшеного зображення.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"threshold\n"
": The color reconstruction module replaces the color of all target pixels having luminance values above this threshold. Only pixels with luminance values below the threshold are taken as valid source pixels for replacement colors. Setting this parameter too high will cause the module to have no effect on any pixels. Setting it too low will minimize the “pool” of replacement colors -- if no suitable colors are available the original colors are maintained. This parameter therefore exhibits a “sweet spot” characteristic with an optimum setting depending on the individual image.\n"
msgstr ""
"поріг\n"
": Модуль відновлення кольору замінює колір усіх цільових пікселів, що мають "
"значення яскравості вище цього порогу. Тільки пікселі зі значеннями "
"освітленості нижче порогового значення приймаються як дійсні джерельні "
"пікселі для кольорів заміни. Якщо встановити цей параметр занадто високим, "
"модуль не матиме впливу на жодні пікселі. Якщо встановити його занадто "
"низьким, мінімізується “пул” кольорів заміни -- якщо відсутні відповідні "
"кольори, оригінальні кольори зберігаються. Тому цей параметр демонструє "
"характеристику “золотої середини” з оптимальним налаштуванням залежно від "
"зображення.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"spatial extent\n"
": The spatial distance that source pixels may have from target pixels in order for them to contribute to color replacement. Higher values cause ever more distant pixels to contribute. This increases the chance of finding a replacement color but makes the replacement color less well defined.\n"
msgstr ""
"просторовий вимір\n"
": Просторова відстань, яку можуть мати джерельні пікселі від цільових "
"пікселів, щоб вони могли сприяти заміні кольорів. Більш високі значення "
"призводять до все більш віддалених пікселів. Це збільшує шанс знайти колір "
"заміни, але робить колір заміни менш чітко визначеним.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"range extent\n"
": The range difference (in luminance) that source pixels may have from target pixels in order for them to contribute to color replacement. Higher values cause more pixels to contribute even if their luminance differs more strongly from the target pixels. This again increases the chance of finding a replacement color but at the same time increases the risk of unfitting colors creeping in.\n"
msgstr ""
"вимір яскравості\n"
": Різниця в діапазоні (в яскравості), яку можуть мати джерельні пікселі від "
"цільових пікселів, щоб вони могли робити внесок в заміну кольорів. Більш "
"високі значення призводять до збільшення кількості пікселів, навіть якщо їх "
"яскравість сильніше відрізняється від цільових пікселів. Це знову збільшує "
"шанс знайти колір заміни, але одночасно збільшує ризик привнесення "
"невідповідних кольорів.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"precedence\n"
": This combobox defines whether certain replacement colors shall take precedence over others as follows:\n"
msgstr ""
"пріоритет\n"
": Цей список визначає, чи мають певні кольори заміщення перевагу над іншими, "
"наступним чином:\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _off_ (default): All pixels contribute equally\n"
": - _saturated colors_: Pixels contribute according to their chromaticity – the more highly-saturated a color, the more it contributes\n"
": - _hue_: give precedence to a specific hue (see below)\n"
msgstr ""
": - _немає_ (за замовчуванням): Внесок усіх пікселів однаковий\n"
": - _насичені кольори_: Внесок пікселів відповідає їх хроматичності - чим "
"сильніше насичений колір, тим більше вага його внеску\n"
": - _відтінок_: надає перевагу певному відтінку (див. нижче)\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": This slider is only visible if you set the _precedence_ to “hue”. It allows you to select a preferred hue for replacement colors. This only has an effect if the preferred hue is actually present within the selected spatial and range distance of the target pixels (see above). A typical use case is repairing highlights on human skin in situations where diverging colors are in close proximity (e.g. textiles or hair with a luminance close that of to skin). Setting a hue preference on skin tones prevents these other colors from creeping in.\n"
msgstr ""
"відтінок\n"
": Цей повзунок видно лише в тому випадку, якщо ви встановите для _пріоритет_ "
"значення “відтінок”. Він дозволяє вибрати бажаний відтінок для кольорів "
"заміни. Це має ефект лише, якщо бажаний відтінок насправді присутній у межах "
"вибраної просторової та діапазонної відстані від цільових пікселів (див. "
"вище). Типовим варіантом використання є відновлення відблисків на шкірі "
"людини в ситуаціях, коли кольори, що розходяться, знаходяться в "
"безпосередній близькості (наприклад, текстиль або волосся з яскравістю, "
"близькою до яскравості шкіри). Встановлення переваги відтінку для відтінків "
"шкіри запобігає проникненню цих інших кольорів.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color calibration"
msgstr "калібрування кольору"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A fully-featured color-space correction, white balance adjustment and channel mixer. This simple yet powerful module can be used in the following ways:\n"
msgstr ""
"Повнофункціональна корекція колірного простору, регулювання балансу білого "
"та змішувач каналів. Цей простий, але потужний модуль можна використовувати "
"наступними способами:\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To adjust the white balance ([chromatic adaptation](#white-balance-in-the-chromatic-adaptation-transformation-cat-tab)), working in tandem with the [_white balance_](./white-balance.md) module. In this case, the _white balance_ module performs an initial white balance step (which is still required in order for the [_demosaic_](./demosaic.md) module to work effectively). The _color calibration_ module then calculates a more perceptually-accurate white balance after the input color profile has been applied.\n"
msgstr ""
"Щоб відрегулювати баланс білого ([хроматична адаптація](#white-balance-in-"
"the-chromatic-adaptation-transformation-cat-tab)), працюючи в тандемі з "
"модулем [_баланс білого_](./white-balance.md). У цьому випадку модуль "
"_баланс білого_ виконує початковий крок балансу білого (який все ще "
"необхідний для ефективної роботи модуля [_демозаїкізація_](./demosaic.md)). "
"Потім модуль _калібрування кольору_ обчислює більш перцептивно точний баланс "
"білого після застосування вхідного колірного профілю.\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As a simple RGB [channel mixer](#channel-mixing), adjusting the output R, G and B channels based on the R, G and B input channels, to perform cross-talk color-grading.\n"
msgstr ""
"Як простий RGB [змішувач каналів](#channel-mixing), що регулює вихідні R, G "
"і B канали на основі вхідних каналів R, G і B, для виконання перехресного "
"грейдингу кольорів.\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To adjust the [color saturation and brightness](#brightness-and-colorfulness-tabs) of the pixels, based on the relative strength of the R, G and B channels of each pixel.\n"
msgstr ""
"Для регулювання [насиченості та яскравості кольорів](#brightness-and-"
"colorfulness-tabs) пікселів, виходячи із відносної сили каналів R, G і B "
"кожного пікселя.\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To produce a [grayscale output](#gray-tab) based on the relative strengths of the R, G and B channels, in a way similar to the response of black and white film to a light spectrum.\n"
msgstr ""
"Для створення [виходу у відтінках сірого](#gray-tab) на основі відносної "
"сили каналів R, G і B, подібно до реакції чорно-білої плівки на спектр "
"світла.\n"

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To improve the color accuracy of the input color profiles using a [color checker](#extracting-settings-using-a-color-checker) chart.\n"
msgstr ""
"Для підвищення точності кольору вхідних кольорових профілів при використанні "
"[калібраційної мішені](#extracting-settings-using-a-color-checker).\n"

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "White Balance in the Chromatic Adaptation Transformation (CAT) tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Chromatic adaptation aims to predict how all surfaces in the scene would look if they had been lit by another illuminant. What we actually want to predict, though, is how those surfaces would have looked if they had been lit by the same illuminant as your monitor, in order to make all colors in the scene match the change of illuminant. White balance, on the other hand, aims only at ensuring that whites and grays are really neutral (R = G = B) and doesn’t really care about the rest of the color range. White balance is therefore only a partial chromatic adaptation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Chromatic adaptation is controlled within the Chromatic Adaptation Transformation (CAT) tab of the _color calibration_ module. When used in this way the _white balance_ module is still required as it needs to perform a basic white balance operation (connected to the input color profile values). This technical white balancing (\"camera reference\" mode) is a flat setting that makes grays lit by a standard D65 illuminant look achromatic, and makes the demosaicing process more accurate, but does not perform any perceptual adaptation according to the scene. The actual chromatic adaptation is then performed by the _color calibration_ module, on top of those corrections performed by the _white balance_ and _input color profile_ modules. The use of custom matrices in the _input color profile_ module is therefore discouraged. Additionally, the RGB coefficients in the _white balance_ module need to be accurate in order for this module to work in a predictable way.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _color calibration_ and _white balance_ modules can be automatically applied to perform chromatic adaptation for new edits by setting the chromatic adaptation workflow option ([preferences > processing > auto-apply chromatic adaptation defaults](../../preferences-settings/processing.md)) to \"modern\". If you prefer to perform all white balancing within the _white balance_ module, a \"legacy\" option is also available. Neither option precludes the use of other modules such as [_color balance_](./color-balance.md) further down the pixel pipeline for creative color grading.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default, _color calibration_ performs chromatic adaptation by:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "reading the RAW file's Exif data to fetch the scene white balance set by the camera,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "adjusting this setting using the camera reference white balance from the _white balance_ module,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "further adjusting this setting with the input color profile in use (standard matrix only).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For consistency, the _color calibration_ module's default settings always assume that the standard matrix is used in the _input color profile_ module -- any non-standard settings in this module are ignored. However, _color calibration_'s defaults can read any auto-applied preset in the _white balance_ module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It is also worth noting that, unlike the _white balance_ module, _color calibration_ can be used with [masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md). This means that you can selectively correct different parts of the image to account for differing light sources.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To achieve this, create an instance of the _color calibration_ module to perform global adjustments using a mask to exclude those parts of the image that you wish to handle differently. Then create a second instance of the module reusing the mask from the first instance (inverted) using a [raster mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/raster.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "CAT tab workflow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The default illuminant and color space used by the chromatic adaptation are initialised from the Exif metadata of the RAW file. There are 4 options available in the CAT tab to set these parameters manually:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Use the color-picker (to the right of the color patch) to select a neutral color from the image or, if one is unavailable, select the entire image. In this case, the algorithm finds the average color within the chosen area and sets that color as the illuminant. This method relies on the \"gray-world\" assumption, which predicts that the average color of a natural scene will be neutral. This method does not work for artificial scenes, for example those with painted surfaces.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select _(AI) detect from edges_, which uses a machine-learning technique to detect the illuminant using the entire image. This algorithm finds the average gradient color over the edges found in the image and sets that color as the illuminant. This method relies on the \"gray-edge\" assumption, which may fail if large chromatic aberrations are present. As with any edge-detection method, it is sensitive to noise and poorly suited to high-ISO images, but it is very well suited for artificial scenes where no neutral colors are available.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select _(AI) detect from surfaces_, which combines the two previous methods also using the entire image. This algorithm finds the average color within the image, giving greater weight to areas where sharp details are found and colors are strongly correlated. This makes it more immune to noise than the _edge_ variant and more immune to legitimate non-neutral surfaces than the naïve average, but sharp colored textures (like green grass) are likely to make it fail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Select _as shot in camera_ to restore the camera defaults and re-read the RAW Exif.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The color patch shows the color of the currently calculated illuminant projected into sRGB space. The aim of the chromatic adaptation algorithm is to turn this color into pure white, which does not necessarily means shifting the image toward its *perceptual* opponent color. If the illuminant is properly set, the image will be given the same tint as shown in the color patch when the module is disabled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To the left of the color patch is the _CCT_ (correlated color temperature) approximation. This is the closest temperature, in kelvin, to the illuminant currently in use. In most image processing software it is customary to set the white balance using a combination of temperature and tint. However, when the illuminant is far from daylight, the CCT becomes inaccurate and irrelevant, and the CIE (International Commission on Illumination) discourages its use in such conditions. The CCT reading informs you of the closest CCT match found:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by _(daylight)_, this means that the current illuminant is close to an ideal daylight spectrum ± 0.5 %, and the CCT figure is therefore meaningful. In this case, you are advised to use the _D (daylight)_ illuminant.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by _(black  body)_, this means that the current illuminant is close to an ideal black body (Planckian) spectrum ± 0.5 %, and the CCT figure is therfore meaningful. In this case, you are advised to use the _Planckian (black body)_ illuminant.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When the CCT is followed by _(invalid)_, this means that the CCT figure is meaningless and wrong, because we are too far from either a daylight or a black body light spectrum. In this case, you are advised to use the _custom_ illuminant. The chromatic adaptation will still perform as expected (see the note below), so the _(invalid)_ tag only means that the current illuminant color is not accurately tied to the displayed CCT. This tag is nothing to be concerned about -- it is merely there to tell you to stay away from the daylight and planckian illuminants because they will not behave as you might expect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When one of the above illuminant detection methods is used, the program checks where the calculated illuminant sits using the 2 idealized spectra (daylight and black body) and chooses the most accurate spectrum model to use in the _illuminant_ parameter. The user-interface will change accordingly:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A temperature slider will be provided if the detected illuminant is close to a _D (daylight)_ or _Planckian (black body)_, for which the CCT is meaningful.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Hue and chroma sliders in CIE 1976 Luv space are offered for the _custom_ illuminant, which allows direct selection of the illuminant color in a perceptual framework without any intermediate assumption.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Internally, the illuminant is represented by its absolute chromaticity coordinates in CIE xyY color space. The illuminant selection options in the module are merely interfaces to set up this chromaticity from real-world relationships and are intended to make this process faster. It does not matter to the actual algorithm if the CCT is tagged \"invalid\" -- this just means that the relationship between the CCT and the corresponding xyY coordinates is not physically accurate. Regardless, the color set for the illuminant, as displayed in the patch, will always be honored by the algorithm.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When switching from one illuminant to another, the module attempts to translate the previous settings to the new illumninant as accurately as possible. Switching from any illuminant to _custom_ preserves your settings entirely, since the _custom_ illuminant is a general case. Switching between other modes, or from _custom_ to any other mode, will not precisely preserve your settings from the previous mode due to rounding errors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Other hard-coded _illuminants_ are available (see below). Their values come from standard CIE illuminants and are absolute. You can use them directly if you know exactly what kind of light bulb was used to illuminate the scene and if you trust your camera's input profile and reference (D65) coefficients to be accurate (otherwise, see _caveats_ below).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "CAT tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"adaptation\n"
": The working color space in which the module will perform its chromatic adaptation transform and channel mixing. The following options are provided:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _Linear Bradford (1985)_: This is accurate for illuminants close to daylight and is compatible with the ICC v4 standard, but produces out-of-gamut colors for more difficult illuminants.\n"
": - _CAT16 (2016)_: This is the default option and is more robust in avoiding imaginary colors while working with large gamut or saturated cyan and purple. It is more accurate than the Bradform CAT in most cases.\n"
": - _Non-linear Bradford (1985)_: This can produce better results than the linear version but is unreliable.\n"
": - _XYZ_: This is the least accurate method and is generally not recommended except for testing and debugging purposes.\n"
": - _none (disable)_: Disable any adaptation and use the pipeline working RGB space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"illuminant\n"
": The type of illuminant assumed to have lit the scene. Choose from the following:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _same as pipeline (D50)_: Do not perform chromatic adaptation in this module instance but perform channel mixing using the selected _adaptation_ color space.\n"
": - _CIE standard illuminant_: Choose from one of the CIE standard illuminants (daylight, incandescent, fluorescent, equi-energy, or black body), or a non-standard \"LED light\" illuminant. These values are all pre-computed -- as long as your camera sensor is properly profiled, you can just use them as-is. For illuminants that lie near the Planckian locus, an additional \"temperature\" control is also provided (see below).\n"
": - _custom_: If a neutral gray patch is available in the image, the color of the illuminant can be selected using the color picker, or can be manually specified using hue and saturation sliders (in LCh perceptual color space). The color swatch next to the color picker shows the color of the calculated illuminant used in the CAT compensation. The color picker can also be used to restrict the area used for AI detection (below).\n"
": - _(AI) detect from image surfaces_: This algorithm obtains the average color of image patches that have a high covariance between chroma channels in YUV space and a high intra-channel variance. In other words, it looks for parts of the image that appear as though they should be gray, and discards flat colored surfaces that may be legitimately non-gray. It also discards chroma noise as well as chromatic aberrations.\n"
": - _(AI) detect from image edges_: Unlike the _white balance_ module's auto-white-balancing which relies on the \"gray world\" assumption, this method auto-detects a suitable illuminant using the \"gray edge\" assumption, by calculating the Minkowski p-norm (p = 8) of the laplacian and trying to minimize it. That is to say, it assumes that edges should have the same gradient over all channels (gray edges). It is more sensitive to noise than the previous surface-based detection method.\n"
": - _as shot in camera_: Calculate the illuminant based on the white balance settings provided by the camera.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"temperature\n"
": Adjust the color temperature of the illuminant. Move the slider to the right to assume a more blue illuminant, which will make the white-balanced image appear warmer/more red. Move the slider to the left to assume a more red illuminant, which makes the image appear cooler/more blue after compensation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": This control is only provided for illuminants that lie near the Planckian locus and provides fine-adjustment along that locus. For other illuminants the concept of \"color temperature\" doesn't make sense, so no temperature slider is provided.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": For custom white balance, set the _hue_ of the illuminant color in LCh color space, derived from CIE Luv space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"chroma\n"
": For custom white balance, set the _chroma_ (or saturation) of the illuminant color in LCh color space, derived from CIE Luv space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"gamut compression\n"
":  Most camera sensors are slightly sensitive to invisible UV wavelengths, which are recorded on the blue channel and produce \"imaginary\" colors. Once corrected by the input color profile, these colors will end up out of gamut (that is, it may no longer be possible to represent certain colors as a valid [R,G,B] triplet with positive values in the working color space) and produce visual artifacts in gradients. The chromatic adaptation may also push other valid colors out of gamut, at the same time pushing any already out-of-gamut colors even further out of gamut. _Gamut compression_ uses a perceptual, non-destructive, method to attempt to compress the saturation while preserving the luminance as-is and the hue as close as possible, in order to fit the whole image into the gamut of the pipeline working color space. One example where this feature is very useful is for scenes containing blue LED lights, which are often quite problematic and can result in ugly gamut clipping in the final image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clip negative RGB from gamut\n"
": Remove any negative RGB values (set them to zero). This helps to deal with bad black level as well as the blue channel clipping issues that may occur with blue LED lights.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "CAT warnings"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The chromatic adaptation in this module relies on a number of assumptions about the earlier processing steps in the pipeline in order to work correctly, and it can be easy to inadvertently break these assumptions in subtle ways. To help you to avoid these kind of mistakes, the _color calibration_ module will show warnings in the following circumstances.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If the _color calibration_ module is set up to perform chromatic adaptation but the _white balance_ module is not set to \"camera reference\", warnings will be shown in both modules. These errors can be resolved either by setting the _white balance_ module to \"camera reference\" or by disabling chromatic adaptation in the _color calibration_ module. Note that some sensors may require minor corrections within the _white balance_ module in which case these warnings can be ignored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If two or more instances of _color calibration_ have been created, each attempting to perform chromatic adaptation, an error will be shown on the second instance. This could be a valid use case (for instance where masks have been set up to apply different white balances to different non-overlapping areas of the image) in which case the warnings can be ignored. For most other cases, chromatic adaptation should be disabled in one of the instances to avoid double-corrections.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "  By default, if an instance of the _color calibration_ module is already performing chromatic adaptation, each new instance you create will automatically have its adaptation set to \"none (bypass)\" to avoid this \"double-correction\" error.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The chromatic adaptation modes in _color calibration_ can be disabled by either setting the _adaptation_ to \"none (bypass)\" or setting the _illuminant_ to \"same as pipeline (D50)\" in the CAT tab.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These warnings are intended to prevent common and easy mistakes while using the automatic default presets in the module in a typical RAW editing workflow. When using custom presets and some specific workflows, such as editing film scans or JPEGs, these warnings can and should be ignored.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "channel mixing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The remainder of this module is a standard channel mixer, allowing you to adjust the output R, G, B, colorfulness, brightness and gray of the module based on the relative strengths of the R, G and B input channels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Channel mixing is performed in the color space defined by the _adaptation_ control on the CAT tab. For all practical purposes, these CAT spaces are particular RGB spaces tied to human physiology and proportional to the light emissions in the scene, but they still behave in the same way as any other RGB space. The use of any of the CAT spaces can make the channel mixer tuning process easier, due to their connection with human physiology, but it is also possible to mix channels in the RGB working space of the pipeline by setting the _adaptation_ to \"none (bypass)\". To perform channel mixing in one of the _adaptation_ color spaces without chromatic adaptation, set the _illuminant_ to \"same as pipeline (D50)\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: The actual colors of the CAT or RGB primaries used for the channel mixing, projected to sRGB display space, are painted in the background of the RGB sliders, so you can get a sense of the color shift that will result from your altered settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Channel mixing is a process that defines a boosting/muting factor for each channel as a ratio of all the original channels. Instead of entering a single flat correction that ties the output value of a channel to its input value (for example, `R_output = R_input × correction`), the correction to each channel is dependent on the input of _all_ of the channels for each pixel (for example, `R_output = R_input × R_correction + G_input × G_correction + B_input × B_correction`). Thus a pixel's channels contribute to each other (a process known as \"cross-talk\") which is equivalent to rotating the primary colors of the color space in 3D. This is, in effect, digital simulation of physical color filters.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Although rotating primary colors in 3D is ultimately equivalent to applying a general hue rotation, the connection between the RGB corrections and the resulting perceptual hue rotation is not directly predictable, which makes the process non-intuitive. \"R\", \"G\" and \"B\" should be taken as a mixture of 3 lights that we dial up and down, not as a set of colors or hues. Also, since RGB tristimulus does not decouple luminance and chrominance, but is an additive lighting setup, the \"G\" channel is more strongly tied to human luminance perception than the \"R\" and \"B\" ones; All pixels have a non-zero G channel, which implies that any correction to the G channel will likely affect all pixels.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The channel mixing process is therefore tied to a physical interpretation of the RGB tristimulus (as additive lights) that makes it well-suited for primary color grading and illuminant corrections, and blends the color changes smoothly. However, trying to understand and predict it from a perceptual point of view (luminance, hue and saturation) is going to fail and is discouraged.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: The \"R\", \"G\" and \"B\" labels on the channels of the color spaces in this module are merely conventions formed out of habit. These channels do not necessarily look \"red\", \"green\" and \"blue\", and users are advised against trying to make sense out of them based on their names. This is a general principle that applies to _any_ RGB space used in any application.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "R, G and B tabs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At its most basic level, you can think of the R, G and B tabs of the _color calibration_ module as a type of matrix multiplication between a 3x3 matrix and the input [R G B] values. This is in fact very similar to what a matrix-based ICC color profile does, except that the user can input the matrix coefficients via the darktable GUI rather than reading the coefficients from an ICC profile file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ Rr Rg Rb ┐     ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ Gr Gg Gb │  X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ Br Bg Bb ┘     └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ Rr Rg Rb ┐     ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ Gr Gg Gb │  X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ Br Bg Bb ┘     └ B_in ┘\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If, for example, you've been provided with a matrix to transform from one color space to another, you can enter the matrix coefficients into the _channel mixer_ as follows:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "select the _red_ tab and then set the Rr, Rg & Rb values using the red, green and blue input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "select the _green_ tab and then set the Gr, Gg & Gb values using the red, green and blue input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "select the _blue_ tab and then set the Br, Bg & Bb values using the red, green and blue input sliders\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the mixing function in _color calibration_ just copies the input [R G B] channels straight over to the matching output channels. This is equivalent to multiplying by the identify matrix:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ 1  0  0 ┐      ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ 0  1  0 │   X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ 0  0  1 ┘      └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""
"┌ R_out ┐     ┌ 1  0  0 ┐      ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"│ G_out │  =  │ 0  1  0 │   X  │ G_in │\n"
"└ B_out ┘     └ 0  0  1 ┘      └ B_in ┘\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To get an intuitive understanding of how the mixing sliders on the red, greeen and blue tabs behave:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _red_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more red. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more cyan.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _green_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more green. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more magenta.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "for the _blue_ destination, adjusting sliders to the right will make the R, G or B areas of the image more blue. Moving the slider to the left will make those areas more yellow.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "R, G, B tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following controls are shown for each of the R, G and B tabs:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input red/green/blue\n"
": Choose how much the input R, G and B channels influence the output channel relating to the tab concerned.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to normalize the coefficients to try to preserve the overall brightness of this channel in the final image as compared to the input image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "brightness and colorfulness tabs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The brightness and colorfulness (color saturation) of pixels in an image can also be adjusted based on the R, G and B input channels. This uses the same basic algorithm that the [_filmic rgb_](filmic-rgb.md) module uses for tone mapping (which preserves RGB ratios) and for midtones saturation (which massages them).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "colorfulness tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input red/green/blue\n"
": Adjust the color saturation of pixels, based on the R, G and B channels of those pixels. For example, adjusting the _input red_ slider will affect the color saturation of pixels containing a lot of red more than colors containing only a small amount of red.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall saturation constant between the input and output images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "brightness tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input red/green/blue\n"
": Adjust the brightness of certain colors in the image, based on the R, G and B channels of those colors. For example, adjusting the _input red_ slider will affect the brightness of colors containing a lot of R channel much more than colors containing only a small amount of R channel. When darkening/brightening a pixel, the ratio of the R, G and B channels for that pixel is maintained, in order to preserve the hue.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall brightness constant between the input and output images.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "gray tab"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Another very useful application of _color calibration_ is the ability to mix the channels together to produce a grayscale output -- a monochrome image. Select the _gray_ tab, and set the red, green and blue sliders to control how much each channel contributes to the brightness of the output. This is equivalent to the following matrix multiplication:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"GRAY_out  =   [ r  g  b ]  X  ┌ R_in ┐\n"
"                              │ G_in │\n"
"                              └ B_in ┘\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/channel-mixer.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When dealing with skin tones, the relative weights of the three channels will affect the level of detail in the image. Placing more weight on red (e.g. [0.9, 0.3, -0.3]) will make for smooth skin tones, whereas emphasising green (e.g. [0.4, 0.75, -0.15]) will bring out more detail. In both cases the blue channel is reduced to avoid emphasising unwanted skin texture.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "gray tab controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input red/green/blue\n"
": Choose how much each of the R, G and B channels contribute to the gray level of the output. The image will only be converted to monochrome if the three sliders add up to some non-zero value. Adding more blue will tend to bring out more details, adding more red will tend to smooth skin tones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"normalize channels\n"
": Select this checkbox to try to keep the overall brightness constant as the sliders are adjusted.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "extracting settings using a color checker"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Since the channel mixer is essentially an RGB matrix (similar to the [_input color profile_](./input-color-profile.md) used for RAW images) it can be used to improve the color accuracy of the input color profile by computing ad-hoc color calibration settings. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These computed settings aim to minimize the color difference between the scene reference and the camera recording in a given lighting situation. This is equivalent to creating a generic ICC color profile but here, the profile is instead stored as module settings that can be saved as presets or styles, to be shared and re-used between images. Such profiles are meant to complement and refine the generic input profile but do not replace it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This feature can assist with:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "handling difficult illuminants, such as low [CRI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_rendering_index) light bulbs, for which a mere white balancing will never suffice,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "digitizing artworks or commercial products where an accurate rendition of the original colors is required,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "neutralizing a number of cameras to the same ground-truth, in multi-camera photo sessions, in order to obtain a consistent base look and share the color editing settings with a consistent final look,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "obtaining a sane color pipeline from the start, nailing white balance and removing any bounced-light color cast at once, with minimal effort and time.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "supported color checker targets"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Users are not currently permitted to use custom targets, but a limited number of verified color checkers (from reputable manufacturers) are provided:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "X-Rite / Gretag MacBeth Color Checker 24 (pre- and post-2014),\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Datacolor SpyderCheckr 24,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Datacolor SpyderCheckr 48.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Users are discouraged from obtaining cheap, off-brand, color targets as color constancy between batches cannot possibly be asserted at such prices. Inaccurate color checkers will only defeat the purpose of color calibration and possibly make things worse.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "IT7 and IT8 charts are not supported since they are hardly portable and not practical for use on-location for ad-hoc profiles. These charts are better suited for creating generic color profiles, undertaken using a standard illuminant, for example with [Argyll CMS](https://encrypted.pcode.nl/blog/index.html%3Fp=594.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note**: X-Rite changed the formula of their pigments in 2014, which slightly altered the color of the patches. Both formulas are supported in darktable, but you should be careful to choose the correct reference for your target. If in doubt, try both and choose the one that yields the lowest average delta E after calibration.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "prequisites"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In order to use this feature you will need to take a test shot of a supported color checker chart, on-location, under appropriate lighting conditions:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "frame the chart in the center 50% of the camera's field, to ensure that the image is free of vignetting,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "ensure that the main light source is far enough from the chart to give an even lighting field over the surface of the chart,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "adjust the angle between the light, chart and lens to prevent reflections and gloss on the color patches,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "adjust the camera exposure such that the white patch has a brightness L of 94-96% in CIE Lab space or a luminance Y of 83-88% in CIE XYZ space. To be safe, you are advised to bracket your exposure between -1 and +1 EV in matrix metering mode, and pick the closest exposed picture during post-production.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If the lighting conditions are close to a standard D50 to D65 illuminant (direct natural light, no colored bounced light), the color checker shot can be used to produce a generic profile that will be suitable for any daylight illuminant with only a slight adjustment of the white balance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If the lighting conditions are peculiar and far from standard illuminants, the color checker shot will be only usable as an ad-hoc profile for pictures taken in the same lighting conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The settings used in color calibration depend on the chosen CAT space and on any color settings defined earlier in the pipe within the _white balance_ and _input color profile_ modules. As such, the results of the profiling (e.g. the RGB channel mixing coefficients) are valid only for a rigid set of _CAT space_, _white balance_ and _input color profile_ settings. If you wish to create a generic style with your profile, don't forget that you will need to include the settings from these modules as well.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Use the following process to create your profile preset/style:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Enable the [_lens correction_](./lens-correction.md) module to correct any vignetting that might mislead the calibration,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "On the bottom of the _color calibration_ module, click on the arrow near the _calibrate with a color checker_ label, to show the controls,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Pick the correct model and manufacturer in the _chart_ drop-down,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In the image preview, an overlay of the chart's patches will appear. Drag the corners of the chart so that they match the visual references (dots or crosses) around the target, to compensate for any perspective distortion,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '5. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click the _refresh_ button to compute the profile,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '6. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Check the _Profile quality report_. If it is \"good\", you can click on the _validation_ button. If not, try changing the optimization strategy and refresh the profile again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '7. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Save the profile in a preset or style, or simply copy & paste the module settings to all of the pictures taken under the same lighting conditions, from within the lighttable view or filmstrip.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** You don't _need_ to use the standard matrix in the _input color profile_ module when performing a calibration, but be aware that the \"as shot in camera\" default white balance will not work properly with any other profile, and that you will need to always use the same input profile whenever you reuse such calibration settings.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "reading the profile report"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The profile report helps you to assess the quality of the calibration. The settings in color calibration are only a \"best fit\" optimization and will never be 100% accurate for the whole color spectrum. We therefore need to track \"how inaccurate\" it is in order to know whether we can trust this profile or not. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Bad profiles can happen and will do more harm than good if used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "delta E and the quality report"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [CIE delta E 2000](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Color_difference#CIEDE2000) (ΔE) is used as a perceptual metric of the error between the reference color of the patches and the color obtained after each step of calibration:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "ΔE = 0 means that there is no error -- the obtained color is exactly the reference color. Unfortunately, this will never happen in practice.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "ΔE = 2.3 is defined as the Just Noticeable Difference (JND).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "ΔE < 2.3 means that the average observer will not be able to tell the difference between the expected reference color and the obtained color. This is a satisfactory result.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "ΔE > 2.3 means that the color difference between the expected reference and the obtained color is noticeable for the average observer. This is unsatisfactory but sometimes unavoidable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The quality report tracks the average and maximum ΔE at the input of the module (before anything is done), after the chromatic adaptation step (white balance only), and at the output of the module (white balance and channel mixing). At each step, the ΔE should be lower than at the previous step, if everything goes as planned.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "profile data"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This comprises the RGB 3×3 matrix and the detected illuminant. These are expressed in the CAT _adaptation_ space defined in the _CAT_ tab and are provided in case you want to export these coefficients to other software. If the detected illuminant is _daylight_ or _black body_, the matrix should be fairly generic and re-usable for other _daylight_ and _black body_ illuminants with the addition of a small white balance adjustment.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "normalization values"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These are the settings that you should define, as-is, for the _exposure_ and _black level correction_ parameters in the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module, in order to obtain the lowest possible error in your profile. This step is optional and is useful only when the utmost precision is required, but beware that it can produce negative RGB values that will be clipped in various places in the pipeline.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "overlay"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![color checker](./color-calibration/color-checker.png#w75)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The chart overlay displays a disc, in the center of each color patch, that represents the expected reference value of that patch, projected into the display RGB space. This helps you to visually assess the difference between the reference and the actual color without having to bother with ΔE values. This visual clue will be reliable only if you set the _exposure_ module as instructed in the _normalization values_ of the profile report.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once the profile has been calibrated, some square patches will be crossed in the background by one or two diagonals:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "patches that are not crossed have ΔE < 2.3 (JND), meaning they are accurate enough that the average observer will be unable to notice the deviation,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "patches crossed with one diagonal have 2.3 < ΔE < 4.6, meaning that they are mildly inaccurate,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "patches crossed with two diagonals have ΔE > 4.6 (2 × JND), meaning that they are highly inaccurate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This visual feedback will help you to set up the optimization trade-off to check which colors are more or less accurate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "enhancing the profile"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Because any calibration is merely a \"best fit\" optimization (using a weighted least-squares method) it is impossible to have all patches within our ΔE < 2.3 tolerance. Therefore, we will need to compromise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _optimize for_ parameter allows you to define an optimization strategy that attempts to increase the profile accuracy in some colors at the expense of others. The following options are available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_none_: Don't use an explicit strategy but rely on the implicit stategy defined by the color checker manufacturer. For example, if the color checker has mostly low-saturation patches, the profile will be more accurate for less-saturated colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_neutral colors_: Give priority to grays and less-saturated colors. This is useful for desperate cases involving cheap fluorescent and LED lightings, having low CRI. However, it may increase the error in highly-saturated colors more than without any profile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_saturated colors_: Give priority to primary colors and highly-saturated colors. This is useful in product and commercial photography, to get brand colors right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_skin and soil colors_, _foliage colors_, _sky and water colors_: Give priority to the chosen hue range. This is useful if the subject of your pictures is clearly defined and has a typical color.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_average delta E_: Attempt to make the color error uniform across the color range and minimize the average perceptual error. This is useful for generic profiles.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_maximum delta E_: Attempt to minimize outliers and large errors, at the expense of the average error. This is useful to get saturated blues back into line.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "No matter what you do, strategies that favor a low average ΔE will usually have a higher maximum ΔE, and vice versa. Also, blues are always the more challenging color range to get correct, so the calibration usually falls back to protecting blues at the expense of everything else, or everything else at the expense of blues.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The ease of obtaining a proper calibration depends on the quality of the scene illuminant (daylight and high CRI should always be favored), the quality of the primary _input color profile_, the _black point compensation_ set in the _exposure_ module, but first and foremost on the mathematical properties of the camera sensor's filter array.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "profile checking"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It is possible to use the _color space check_ button (first on the left, at the bottom of the module) to perform a single ΔE computation of the color checker reference against the output of the _color calibration_ module. This can be used in the following ways:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To check the accuracy of a profile calculated in particular conditions against a color checker shot in different conditions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To evaluate the performance of any color correction performed earlier in the pipe, by setting the _color calibration_ parameters to values that effectively disable it (CAT _adaptation_ to _none_, everything else set to default), and just use the average ΔE as a performance metric.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "caveats"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The ability to use standard CIE illuminants and CCT-based interfaces to define the illuminant color depends on sound default values for the standard matrix in the _input color profile_ module as well as reasonable RGB coefficients in the _white balance_ module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Some cameras, most notably those from Olympus and Sony, have unexpected white balance coefficients that will always make the detected CCT invalid even for legitimate daylight scene illuminants. This error most likely comes from issues with the standard input matrix, which is taken from the Adobe DNG Converter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "It is possible to alleviate this issue, if you have a computer screen calibrated for D65 illuminant, using the following process:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '1. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Display a white surface on your screen, for example by opening a blank canvas in any photo editing software you like\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '2. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Take a blurry (out of focus) picture of that surface with your camera, ensuring that you don't have any \"parasite\" light in the frame, you have no clipping, and using an aperture between f/5.6 and f/8,\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '3. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Open the picture in darktable and extract the white balance by using the spot tool in the _white balance_ module on the center area of the image (non-central regions might be subject to chromatic aberrations). This will generate a set of 3 RGB coefficients.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '4. '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-calibration.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "[Save a preset](../../darkroom/processing-modules/presets.md#creating-and-editing-presets) for the _white balance_ module with these coefficients and auto-apply it to any color RAW image created by the same camera.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "chromatic aberrations"
msgstr "хроматичні аберації"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Correct chromatic aberrations.\n"
msgstr "Виправляє хроматичні аберації.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As this module operates on non-demosaiced raw data, the underlying model assumes an uncropped photographic image as input. It is therefore likely to fail when you zoom in, as it is only able to operate on the visible portion of the image. The module will therefore be bypassed at high zoom levels, and a \"bypassed\" message will appear at the top of the module. This limitation only applies to interactive work and not to the final export. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module currently only works for images recorded with a Bayer sensor (the sensor used in the majority of cameras). It will not apply any corrections to photos that have been identified as monochrome (see [developing monochrome images](../../guides-tutorials/monochrome.md) for more information).\n"
msgstr ""
"Наразі цей модуль працює лише для зображень, записаних за допомогою сенсора "
"Баєра (сенсор, що використовується у більшості камер). Він не "
"застосовуватиме жодних виправлень до фотографій, які були визначені як "
"монохромні (див. [обробка монохромних зображень](../../guides-tutorials/"
"monochrome.md) для отримання додаткової інформації).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"iterations\n"
": The number of iterations. For most images, \"twice\" is sufficient, and is the default value. Occasionally, increasing this control can give better results.\n"
msgstr ""
"проходи\n"
": Кількість ітерацій. Для більшості зображень достатньо \"два\" і це є "
"значенням за замовчуванням. Іноді збільшення кількості проходів може дати "
"кращі результати.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/chromatic-aberrations.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"avoid colorshift\n"
": If the module causes purple tinting, tick this box to apply a correction.\n"
msgstr ""
"уникати зміщення кольорів\n"
": Якщо модуль викликає пурпурне обарвлення, поставте цей прапорець, щоб "
"застосувати виправлення.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "graduated density"
msgstr "градієнтний фільтр"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate a graduated density filter in order to correct exposure and color in a progressive manner.\n"
msgstr ""
"Імітує фільтр із градуйованою щільністю, щоб поступово коригувати експозицію "
"та колір.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A line is shown on screen allowing the position and rotation of the gradient to be modified with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""
"На екрані відображається лінія, що дозволяє змінювати положення та обертання "
"градієнта за допомогою миші.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module is known to provoke banding artifacts under certain conditions. You should consider activating the [_dithering_](./dithering.md) module to alleviate these issues.\n"
msgstr ""
"Відомо, що цей модуль провокує появу артефактів бандингу за певних умов. Вам "
"слід розглянути можливість активації модуля [_дизеринг_](./dithering.md) для "
"усунення цих проблем.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"density\n"
": Set the density of the filter (EV). A low value underexposes slightly whereas a high value creates a strong filter.\n"
msgstr ""
"щільність\n"
": Встановлює щільність фільтра (EV). Низьке значення недоекспонує слабко, "
"тоді як велике створює сильний фільтр.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hardness\n"
": The progressiveness of the gradient. A low value creates a smooth transition, whereas a high value makes the transition more abrupt.\n"
msgstr ""
"жорсткість\n"
": Прогресивність градієнта. Низьке значення створює плавний перехід, тоді як "
"високе значення робить перехід більш різким.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rotation\n"
": The rotation of the filter. Negative values rotate clockwise. The rotation can also be set by dragging the end of the gradient line with the mouse.\n"
msgstr ""
"обертання\n"
": Обертання фільтра. Негативні значення обертають за годинниковою стрілкою. "
"Обертання також можна встановити, перетягуючи кінець градієнтної лінії за "
"допомогою миші.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": Choose a hue to add a color cast to the gradient.\n"
msgstr ""
"відтінок\n"
": Виберіть відтінок, щоб додати обарвлення до градієнта.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/graduated-density.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of the color cast to add to the gradient (defaults to a neutral color cast of 0)\n"
msgstr ""
"насиченість\n"
": Насиченість обарвлення, яке додається до градієнта (за замовчуванням "
"нейтральне обарвлення, тобто 0)\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lut 3D"
msgstr "lut 3D"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A 3D LUT is a tridimensional table which is used to transform a given RGB value into another RGB value, and is normally used for film simulation and color grading.\n"
msgstr ""
"3D LUT - це тривимірна таблиця, яка використовується для перетворення "
"заданого значення RGB в інше значення RGB, і зазвичай використовується для "
"імітації плівки та грейдингу кольорів.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module accepts `.cube` and `.png` (haldclut) files. The 3D LUT data is not saved in the database or the XMP file, but is instead saved to the 3D LUT file path inside the 3D LUT root folder. This means that it is important to back up your 3D LUT folder properly. Sharing an image with its XMP is useless if the recipient doesn't also have the same 3D LUT file in their own 3D LUT folder.\n"
msgstr ""
"Цей модуль приймає файли `.cube` та ` .png` (haldclut). Дані з цих 3D LUT не "
"зберігаються в базі даних або файлі XMP, а натомість зберігається шлях до "
"файлу 3D LUT усередині кореневої папки 3D LUT. Це означає, що важливо "
"правильно створити резервну копію папки 3D LUT. Немає сенсу ділитися "
"зображенням спільно з файлом XMP, якщо одержувач не має того самого файлу 3D "
"LUT у власній папці 3D LUT.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"file selection\n"
": Choose the 3D LUT file to use. File selection is inactive until the 3D LUT root folder has been defined in [preferences > processing](../../preferences-settings/processing.md).\n"
msgstr ""
"вибір файлу\n"
": Виберіть файл 3D LUT для використання. Вибір файлу неактивний, доки "
"коренева папка 3D LUT не буде визначена в [налаштування> обробка"
"](../../preferences-settings/processing.md).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"application color space\n"
": A 3D LUT is defined relative to a specific color space. Choose the color space for which the selected 3D LUT file has been built. Cube files are usually related to REC.709 while most others are related to sRGB.\n"
msgstr ""
"застосовується в колірному просторі\n"
": 3D LUT визначається щодо певного колірного простору. Виберіть колірний "
"простір, для якого було створено вибраний файл 3D LUT. Файли .cube зазвичай "
"відносяться до REC.709, тоді як більшість інших - до sRGB.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lut-3D.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interpolation\n"
": This defines how to calculate output colors when input colors are not exactly on a node of the RGB cube described by the 3D LUT. There are three interpolation methods available: tetrahedral (default), trilinear and pyramid. Usually you won't see any difference between interpolation methods except with smaller sized LUTs.\n"
msgstr ""
"інтерполяція\n"
": Це визначає спосіб обчислення вихідних кольорів, коли вхідні кольори не є "
"точно на вузлі куба RGB, описаному 3D LUT. Доступні три методи інтерполяції: "
"тетраедричний (за замовчуванням), трилінійний та пірамідальний. Зазвичай ви "
"не побачите ніякої різниці між методами інтерполяції, за винятком LUT менших "
"розмірів.\n"

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/watermark.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "watermark"
msgstr "водяний знак"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/watermark.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Render a vector-based overlay onto your image. Watermarks are standard SVG documents and can be designed using [Inkscape](http://www.inkscape.org/).\n"
msgstr ""
"Візуалізує векторне накладання на ваше зображення. Водяні знаки є "
"стандартними документами SVG і можуть бути розроблені за допомогою "
"[Inkscape](http://www.inkscape.org/).\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/watermark.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The SVG processor of darktable can also substitute strings within the SVG document, which allows you to include image dependent information in the watermark.\n"
msgstr ""
"Обробник SVG в darktable може також замінювати рядки в документі SVG, що "
"дозволяє включати інформацію, залежну від зображення, у водяний знак.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/watermark.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "User-designed watermarks should be placed into the directory `$HOME/.config/darktable/watermarks`. Once in place, use the reload button update the list of available watermarks.\n"
msgstr ""
"Розроблені користувачем водяні знаки слід розміщувати в каталозі `$HOME/."
"config/darktable/watermarks`. Коли файл буде розміщено, за допомогою кнопки "
"перезавантаження оновіть список доступних водяних знаків.\n"

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/watermark.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following is a list of variable strings that are supported for substitution within the SVG document. \n"
msgstr ""
"Далі наведено перелік змінних, які підтримуються для заміни в документі SVG. "
"\n"

#. type: Plain text
