#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Cloning allows us to hide part of an image by replacing it with an area copied from another part of the image. For example, we may wish to get rid of a small cloud in a blue sky:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-original](./retouch/rt-original.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The simplest way to do this is with the _basic cloning_ tool (![retouch-clone-icon](./retouch/rt-clone-icon.png#icon)) -- simply take a circle of blue sky next to the cloud, and use it to paint over the cloud we want to hide:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-clone](./retouch/rt-clone.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "However, if the sample we take doesn't precisely match the surroundings of the item we want to clone out, the result can look a bit jarring. In our example, the sample of sky we chose to use (the clone \"source\" patch) was slightly darker than the piece of sky we wanted to replace (the \"target\" patch):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-clone-nocontrol](./retouch/rt-clone-nocontrol.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If we instead use the _heal_ tool (![retouch-heal-icon](./retouch/rt-heal-icon.png#icon)), the color and luma of the sample is blended to fit better with the surroundings. In our example, using _heal_ instead of _clone_ gives a much more uniform-looking result:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-heal-nocontrol](./retouch/rt-heal-nocontrol.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "fill and blur"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _clone_ and _heal_ tools both require us to specify another part of the image, which is used to \"fill in\" the region we want to hide. Sometimes there is no suitable sample in the image that we can use to fill over the spot. In such cases, the _retouch_ module offers two further options:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-fill-icon](./retouch/rt-fill-icon.png#icon) fill tool\n"
": This tool will fill in the selected region using a chosen color.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-blur-icon](./retouch/rt-blur-icon.png#icon) blur tool\n"
": This tool applies a blur to the selected region, smoothing out any detail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These two options are most useful when used together with wavelet decomposition, where they can be used to smooth over features within a selected detail layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "source and target shapes"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When you activate the _clone_ or _heal_ tool, you will place one or more matching pairs of shapes on the image, each consisting of a target region to be repaired, and a source region to use to undertake that repair. You must first choose the shape you wish to use (you can choose from _circle_, _ellipse_, _path_ or _brush_ -- see the [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) section for details) and (except when using the path shape), an outline of the shape will appear under the cursor.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "While you hover over the image with your mouse, a small plus sign (+) will be shown somewhere on the image, marking where the source shape will be placed by default. This plus sign will either be in a fixed position on the image or will move about with your cursor depending on whether the last pair of shapes was placed using absolute or relative mode (see below). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-source-cross](./retouch/rt-source-cross.png)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The source and target shapes can be placed onto the image in the following ways:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the image to begin placing the target shape (see the [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) section for details on how to draw shapes). The source shape will be placed at the position of the \"plus\" (+) sign on the image and can be adjusted later.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Shift+click to change the position of the source shape in \"relative mode\". The position of the \"plus\" (+) symbol will move to the clicked location. Then move the mouse and Click to begin placing the target shape. If you place subsequent shapes without changing the target location, the source shape will be placed at the same offset from the target shape as was used for the first stroke.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Ctrl+Shift+click to change the position of the source shape in \"absolute\" mode. As above, the position of the \"plus\" (+) symbol will move to the clicked location and you can then place your target shape. If you place subsequent shapes without changing the target location, exactly the same source position will be used, fixed in the absolute coordinate system of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For _circle_ and _ellipse_ shapes only, you can simply click on the desired target location and then drag, releasing your mouse button when you reach the desired source location. This operation does not affect the placement of subsequent shapes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The positions of the source and target shapes may then be altered manually.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "retouch with wavelet decomposition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Wavelets allow us to decompose an image into different layers with varying levels of detail, so that we can work on the layers independently and then recombine them at the end. This is particularly useful in portrait photography, where we are able to deal with skin blotches and blemishes on a coarse layer of detail, while leaving the skin texture in a finer layer of detail untouched. The [_wavelets_](../../darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md) section provides an example of how wavelets decompose the image into detail layers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Through this method, we could for example use the healing tool to paint over a spot that appears in one of the coarse detail layers, while leaving the whiskers in the fine detail layers intact:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-beard-preserve](./retouch/rt-beard-preserve.jpg#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![retouch-overview](./retouch/rt-overview.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "retouch tools"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _retouch tools_ section consists of two items:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shapes\n"
": The number after the _shapes_ label indicates how many shapes have been placed on the image, either directly or within a wavelet layer. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Click on one of the shape icons to draw a new shape on the image (see [drawn masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn.md) for details). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Ctrl+click on a shape icon to draw multiple shapes continuously (right-click to cancel). \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Click the _show and edit shapes_ button (![retouch-shapes-icon](./retouch/rt-shapes-icon.png#icon)) to show all existing shapes for the currently-selected wavelet scale (see below) and edit them.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"algorithms\n"
": Choose a retouching algorithm: clone, heal, fill or blur (see above for details).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "wavelet decompose"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The _wavelet decompose_ section centres around a bar graph showing how the image has been decomposed into different detail (scale) layers. The key features of the bar graph are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The black square on the left represents the entire non-decomposed image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The gray squares show the various wavelet layers, with fine details to the left, and coarse details to the right.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The white square on the right represents the residual image (the remainder of the image after the detail layers have been extracted).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A light gray dot in a square indicates the currently-selected layer. Click on another square to select a different layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The light gray bar running along the top indicates which levels of detail are visible at the current zoom level. Zoom in closer to see the finer levels of detail.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The triangle at the bottom shows how many layers the image has been decomposed into. Drag the triangle to the right to create more layers. Drag it to the left to decrease the number of layers. By default no wavelet decomposition is performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The triangle at the top shows the current value of the \"merge from\" parameter (see below)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The orange lines under the squares indicate which layers have retouching edits applied.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The remaining items in this ection are:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scales\n"
": Indicates how many detail layers the image has been decomposed into. Zero indicates that no wavelet decomposition has been performed.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"current\n"
": Indicates which layer is currently selected (also marked with the light gray dot on the bar graph).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"merge from\n"
": This setting allows a common edit to be applied to multiple consecutive scales within a group starting from the coarsest scale (not including the residual image) down to the scale selected. For example, if \"merge from\" is set to 3 and the maximum scale is 5 then all edits that are added to scale 5 will be applied to scales 3 to 5. Edits added to scale 4 will be applied to scales 3 and 4, and edits added to scale 3 will be applied only to scale 3. If you set _merge from_ to 0, then merging is disabled, and all edits apply only to the scale that are defined in. Setting _merge from_ to the highest scale (in this example, 5) would also effectively disable any merging.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"           merge_from\n"
"               v\n"
"   0   1   2   3   4   5    scale\n"
"               <-------o    scale 5 edits\n"
"               <---o        scale 4 edits\n"
"               o            scale 3 edits\n"
"           o                scale 2 edits\n"
"       o                    scale 1 edits\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-display-icon](./retouch/rt-display-icon.png#icon) display wavelet scale\n"
": Toggles whether to display the currently-selected wavelet layer on the center image. Selecting this option brings up an additional control -- _preview single scale_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"preview single scale\n"
": An additional control that allows the black, white and gray points of the wavelet scale preview to be adjusted to make it easier to see. Click the ![auto-levels-icon](./retouch/rt-auto-levels-icon.png#icon) to set them automatically. This does not affect the module's operation -- only the wavelet scale preview.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-cut-icon](./retouch/rt-cut-icon.png#icon) cut\n"
": Place all shapes on the currently-selected layer onto the clipboard so they can be moved to another layer\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-paste-icon](./retouch/rt-paste-icon.png#icon) paste\n"
": Move the shapes on the clipboard to the currently-selected layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-hide-icon](./retouch/rt-hide-icon.png#icon) temporarily switch off shapes\n"
": Toggle all shapes (whether on the current layer or not) on or off, so temporarily removing the module's effect.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"![retouch-mask-icon](./retouch/rt-mask-icon.png#icon) display masks\n"
": Show the target shapes associated with the currently-selected layer with a yellow overlay.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This section allows you to modify settings related to the currently-selected shape:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shape selected\n"
": Indicates which shape is currently selected, and what type of shape it is.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fill mode\n"
": If the _fill_ algorithm has been selected for the currently-selected shape, choose whether to \"erase\" or fill the selected shape with a chosen \"color\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"fill color\n"
": If a _fill mode_ of \"color\" has been selected, choose which color to fill the shape with. You can click to select or enter a custom rgb value or use the color picker to take a sample from the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"brightness\n"
": If a _fill_ algorithm has been selected, fine-tune the color's brightness. This slider also works in \"erase\" mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur type\n"
": If the _blur_ algorithm has been selected for the currently-selected shape, choose whether to use a \"gaussian\" or \"bilateral\" blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blur radius\n"
": If the _blur_ algorithm has been selected for the currently-selected shape, choose the radius of the blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mask opacity\n"
": Alter the opacity of the mask associated with the currently-selected shape. An opacity of 1.000 indicates the shape is completely opaque and the module's effect is fully applied, whereas a value less than 1.000 indicates that the effect applied by the shape is blended with the underlying image to the degree indicated by the slider.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "invert (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is deprecated in darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_negadoctor_](./negadoctor.md) module instead.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Invert scanned negatives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/invert.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color of film material\n"
": Clicking on the colored field will open a color selector dialog which offers you a choice of commonly used colors, or allows you to define an RGB color. You can also activate the color picker to take a color probe from your image – preferably from the unexposed border of your negative.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "zone system (deprecated)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Please note that this module is deprecated in darktable 3.4 and should no longer be used for new edits. Please use the [_tone equalizer_](./tone-equalizer.md) or multiple instances of the [_exposure_](./exposure.md) module with [parametric masks](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/parametric.md) to narrow down on a zone.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Adjust the lightness of an image using Ansel Adams' [zone system](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zone_System).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The lightness of the image (the L channel in Lab color space) is divided into a number of zones ranging from pure black to pure white. These zones are displayed in a zonebar beneath a preview image. The number of zones can be changed by mouse-scrolling on that bar (default 10 zones).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![zone-system](./zone-system/zone-system.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The zonebar is split horizontally with the lower part showing the zones of the module's input and the upper part the zones of the module's output. In its default state both parts are fully aligned. While the output zones are static you can left click and drag a control point in the input zones to modify the mapping between input and output. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Shifting a control point proportionally expands the zones on one side and compresses the zones on the other side of that point. All pre-existing control points stay in place, effectively preventing changes to the zones beyond the next control point. Use right click to remove a control point. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/zone-system.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The preview image above the zonebar shows how the image's zones are broken down. When hovering above a zone, that zone – either from input or output – is highlighted in yellow on the preview image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "lowlight vision"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Simulate human lowlight vision making pictures look closer to human lowlight perception. This module can also be used to perform a day-to-night conversion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The idea is to calculate a [scotopic vision](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotopic_vision) image, which is perceived by the rods rather than than the cones in the eyes under low light. Scotopic lightness is then mixed with photopic value (regular color image pixel) using some blending function. This module is also able to simulate the [Purkinje effect](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purkinje_effect) by adding some blueness to the dark parts of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This module comes with several presets which can be used to get a better idea of how the module works.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"curve\n"
": The horizontal axis represents pixel lightness from dark (left) to bright (right). The vertical axis represents the kind of vision from night vision (bottom) to day vision (top).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/lowlight-vision.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"blue\n"
": Set the blue hint in shadows (Purkinje effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-correction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "color correction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Modify the global image saturation to give the image a tint or as an alternative method to split-tone the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"color board\n"
": For split toning move the white dot to the desired highlight tint and then select a tint for shadows with the dark spot. For a simple global tint set both spots to the same color.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/color-correction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": Correct the global saturation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "colorize"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Add a solid layer of color to the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"hue\n"
": The hue of the color layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"saturation\n"
": The saturation of shadow tones.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"lightness\n"
": The lightness of the color layer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/colorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"source mix\n"
": Controls how the lightness of the input image is mixed with the color layer. Setting this to zero will result in a uniformly colored plane.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "censorize"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Degrade parts of the image in an aesthetically pleasing way, to anonymize people/objects or hide body parts to comply with social media censorship.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Censorize works in linear RGB to apply physically-accurate gaussian blur and gaussian luminance noise.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Aside from anonymization, this module can also be used for a wide range of creative purposes, for example:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Combine a simple blur with a multiply [blend mode](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/blend-modes/) to create a realistic bloom (Orton effect).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Combine a simple blur with a subtract blending mode and low opacity to create an [unsharp mask](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unsharp_masking), similar to the [sharpen](./sharpen.md) module but in an RGB scene-referred space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Add noise to create artificial grain.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** The anonymizing methods provided by this module are not forensically safe in order to favor aesthetics. Some forensic techniques may still be able to reconstruct the censorized content based on its structure, especially for simple shapes and text (e.g. license plates, street numbers).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If forensically safe anonymization is required, the only way to achieve this is to paint the surfaces with a solid color. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**The darktable team does not accept responsability for poorly anonymized pictures leading to the identification of individuals or personal property.**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "workflow"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You are advised to leave the module's controls at their default values while you [mask](../../darkroom/masking-and-blending/masks/drawn/) the areas of the image that you wish to censorize, in order that the details of the image remain visible.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"input blur radius\n"
": The strength of the first pass of the gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"pixellation radius\n"
": The size of the \"big pixels\" created after the first pass of gaussian blur.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"output blur radius\n"
": The strength of the second pass of the gaussian blur, applied after the pixellation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/censorize.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"noise level\n"
": The strength (standard deviation) of the luminance gaussian noise applied after the second pass of the gaussian blur. Adding noise can fake details in the blurred regions and make content detection more difficult for artificial intelligence algorithms.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "highlight reconstruction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Attempt to reconstruct color information for pixels that are clipped in one or more RGB channel. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If these pixels are left partially clipped it can result in unrealistic colors appearing in the image. For example pixels with both green and blue channels clipped will appear to be red without any highlight reconstruction.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Three methods of reconstruction are available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clip highlights\n"
": Clamp all pixels to the white level (i.e. clip the remaining color channels). This method is most useful in cases where clipped highlights occur in naturally desaturated objects (e.g. clouds).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"reconstruct in LCh\n"
": Analyse each pixel with at least one clipped channel and attempt to correct the clipped pixel (in LCh color space) using the values of the other (3 for Bayer or 8 for X-Trans) pixels in the affected sensor block. The reconstructed highlights will still be monochrome, but brighter and with more detail than with “clip highlights”. This method works fairly well with a high-contrast base curve, which renders highlights desaturated. As with _clip highlights_ this method is a good option for naturally desaturated objects.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"reconstruct color\n"
": Use an algorithm that transfers color information from unclipped surroundings into the clipped highlights. This method works very well on areas with homogeneous colors and is especially useful on skin tones with smoothly fading highlights. Please note that this method can produce maze-like artifacts on highlights behind high-contrast edges, for example well-exposed fine structures in front of an overexposed background.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "For highlight reconstruction to be effective you need to also apply a negative EV correction in the [exposure](./exposure.md) module\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "When using the highlight reconstruction included with the [filmic rgb](./filmic-rgb.md) module it may be useful to disable this module so that filmic has more information to work with.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"method\n"
": Choose the method for highlight reconstruction (see above)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/highlight-reconstruction.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"clipping threshold\n"
": Manually adjust the clipping threshold against magenta highlights. You shouldn't need to adjust this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "split-toning"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Create a two color linear toning effect where the shadows and highlights are represented by two different colors.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The split-toning module does not convert images to black and white and has limited benefits on color images. In order to perform traditional split-toning, the input to this module should therefore be monochrome.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"shadows and highlights color\n"
": Set the desired hue and saturation for both shadows and highlights. Clicking on the colored squares will open a color selector dialog which offers you a choice of commonly used colors, or allows you to define a color in RGB color space.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"balance\n"
": The ratio of toning between shadows and highlights. When set to 50%, half of the lightness range in image is used for shadows toning and the other half for highlights toning.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/module-reference/processing-modules/split-toning.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"compression\n"
": The percentage of total (mid-tone) lightness range that is not affected by color toning. This compresses the effect on the shadows and highlights while preserving the mid-tones.\n"
msgstr ""

