#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/a-simple-example.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Start darktable and you will see the sentence \"`Hello World !`\" printed on the console. Nothing fancy but it's a start.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/a-simple-example.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At this point, there is nothing darktable-specific in the script. We simply use Lua's standard print function to print a string. That's nice and all, but we can do better than that. To access the darktable API you first need to `require` it and save the returned object in a variable. Once this is done you can access the darktable API as subfields of the returned object. All of this is documented in darktable's [Lua API](./api.md) reference manual.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/a-simple-example.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"local darktable = require \"darktable\"\n"
"darktable.print_error(\"Hello World !\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/a-simple-example.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Run the script and ... nothing happens. The function `darktable.print_error` is just like `print` but will only print the message if you have enabled lua traces by running darktable with \"`darktable -d lua`\" on the command line. This is the recommended way to do traces in a darktable lua script.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/lua/basic-principles.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "basic principles: luarc files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/basic-principles.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At startup, darktable will automatically run the Lua scripts `$DARKTABLE/share/darktable/luarc` and `$HOME/.config/darktable/luarc` (where `$DARKTABLE` represents the darktable installation directory and `$HOME` represents your home directory).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/basic-principles.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This is the only time darktable will run Lua scripts by itself. These scripts can register callbacks to perform actions on various darktable events. This callback mechanism is the primary method of triggering lua actions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "adding a simple shortcut"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "So far, all our scripts have done things during startup. This is of limited use and doesn't allow us to react to real user actions. To do more advanced things we need to register a function that will be called on a given event. The most common event to react to is a keyboard shortcut.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darktable = require \"darktable\"\n"
"\n"
"local function hello_shortcut(event, shortcut)\n"
"darktable.print(\"Hello, I just received '\"..event..\n"
"       \"' with parameter '\"..shortcut..\"'\")\n"
"end\n"
"\n"
"darktable.register_event(\"shortcut\",hello_shortcut,\n"
"       \"A shortcut that prints its parameters\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Now start darktable, go to  \"preferences > shortcuts > lua > A shortcut that prints its parameters\", assign a shortcut and try it. You should see a nice message printed on the screen.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Let's look at the code in detail. We first define a function which takes two strings as input parameters. The first one is the type of event that is triggered ( \"shortcut\" ) and the second one is the name of the shortcut ( \"A shortcut that prints its parameters\" ). The function itself calls `darktable.print`, which will print the message as an overlay in the main window.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once that function is defined, we register it as a shortcut callback. To do that we call `darktable.register_event` which is a generic function for all types of events. We tell it that we are registering a shortcut event, then we give the callback to call and last, we give the string to use to describe the shortcut in the preferences window.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Let's try a shortcut that is a little more interactive. This one will look at the images the user is currently interested in (selected or moused-over) and increase their rating.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darktable = require \"darktable\"\n"
"\n"
"darktable.register_event(\"shortcut\",function(event,shortcut)\n"
"    local images = darktable.gui.action_images\n"
"    for _,v in pairs(images) do\n"
"      v.rating = v.rating + 1\n"
"    end\n"
"  end,\"Increase the rating of an image\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At this point, most of this code should be self explanatory. Just a couple of notes:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Instead of declaring a function and referencing it, we declare it directly in the call to `darktable.register_event` this is strictly equivalent but slightly more compact.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "`image.rating` is a field that gives the star rating of any image (between 0 and 5 stars, -1 means rejected).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "`darktable.gui.action_images` is a table containing all the images of interest. darktable will act on selected images if any image is selected, and on the image under the mouse if no image is selected. This function makes it easy to follow darktable's UI logic in lua.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "If you select an image and press your shortcut a couple of times, it will work correctly at first but when you have reached five stars, darktable will start showing the following error on the console: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"<![CDATA[\n"
"LUA ERROR : rating too high : 6\n"
"stack traceback:\n"
"   [C]: in ?\n"
"   [C]: in function '__newindex'\n"
"  ./configdir/luarc:10: in function <./configdir/luarc:7>\n"
"      LUA ERROR : rating too high : 6\n"
"  ]]>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid " This is lua's way of reporting errors. We have attempted to set a rating of 6 to an image, but a rating can only go as high as 5. It would be trivial to add a check, but let's go the complicated way and catch the error instead:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darktable.register_event(\"shortcut\",function(event,shortcut)\n"
"    local images = darktable.gui.action_images\n"
"    for _,v in pairs(images) do\n"
"      result,message = pcall(function()\n"
"        v.rating = v.rating + 1\n"
"        end)\n"
"      if not result then\n"
"        darktable.print_error(\"could not increase rating of image \"..\n"
"          tostring(v)..\" : \"..message)\n"
"      end\n"
"    end\n"
"end,\"Increase the rating of an image\")\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/simple-shortcut.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "`pcall` will run its first argument and catch any exception thrown by it. If there is no exception it will return `true` plus any result returned by the function; if there is an exception it will return `false` and the error message of the exception. We simply test these results and print them to the console.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Lua scripts can be used to define actions for darktable to perform when an event is triggered. One example might be calling an external application during file export in order to apply additional processing steps outside of darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "[Lua](http://www.lua.org/) is an independent project founded in 1993, providing a powerful, fast, lightweight, embeddable scripting language. Lua is widely used by many open source applications, in commercial programs, and for games programming.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "darktable uses Lua version 5.3. Describing the principles and syntax of Lua is beyond the scope of this usermanual. For a detailed introduction see the [Lua reference manual](http://www.lua.org/manual/5.3/manual.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/overview.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following sections will provide you with a brief introduction to how Lua scripts can be used within darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "sharing scripts"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "So far, all of our lua code has been in _luarc_. That's a good way to develop your script but not very practical for distribution. We need to make this into a proper lua module. To do that, we save the code in a separate file (`scp-storage.lua` in this case):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"--[[\n"
"SCP STORAGE\n"
"a simple storage to export images via scp\n"
"\n"
"AUTHOR\n"
"Jérémy Rosen (jeremy.rosen@enst-bretagne.fr)\n"
"\n"
"INSTALLATION\n"
"* copy this file in $CONFIGDIR/lua/ where CONFIGDIR\n"
"is your darktable configuration directory\n"
"* add the following line in the file $CONFIGDIR/luarc\n"
"  require \"scp-storage\"\n"
"\n"
"USAGE\n"
"* select \"Export via SCP\" in the storage selection menu\n"
"* set the target directory \n"
"* export your images\n"
"\n"
"LICENSE\n"
"GPLv2\n"
"\n"
"]]\n"
"darktable = require \"darktable\"\n"
"darktable.configuration.check_version(...,{2,0,0})\n"
"\n"
"local scp_path = darktable.new_widget(\"entry\"){\n"
"  tooltip =\"Complete path to copy to. Can include user and hostname\",\n"
"  text = \"\",\n"
"  reset_callback = function(self) self.text = \"\" end\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"darktable.register_storage(\"scp_export\",\"Export via scp\",\n"
"  function( storage, image, format, filename,\n"
"     number, total, high_quality, extra_data)\n"
"    if coroutine.yield(\"RUN_COMMAND\",\"scp \"..filename..\" \"..\n"
"      scp_path.text\n"
"    ) then\n"
"      darktable.print_error(\"scp failed for \"..tostring(image))\n"
"    end\n"
"    end,\n"
"    nil, --finalize\n"
"    nil, --supported\n"
"    nil, --initialize\n"
"    darktable.new_widget(\"box\") {\n"
"    orientation =\"horizontal\",\n"
"    darktable.new_widget(\"label\"){label = \"target SCP PATH \"},\n"
"    scp_path,\n"
"})\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "darktable will look for scripts (following the normal lua rules) in the standard directories plus `$CONFIGDIR/lua/*.lua`. So our script can be called by simply adding `require \"scp-storage\"` in the _luarc_ file. A couple of extra notes...\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The function `darktable.configuration.check_version` will check compatibility for you. The \"`...`\" will turn into your script's name and `{2,0,0}` is the API version you have tested your script with. You can add multiple API versions if you update your script for multiple versions of darktable.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Make sure to declare all your functions as `local` so as not to pollute the general namespace.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Make sure you do not leave debug prints in your code -- `darktable.print_error` in particular allows you to leave debug prints in your final code without disturbing the console.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You are free to choose any license for your script but scripts that are uploaded on darktable's website need to be GPLv2.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/sharing-scripts.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Once you have filled all the fields, checked your code, you can upload it to our script page [here](https://github.com/darktable-org/lua-scripts).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "using darktable from a lua script"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "_Warning: This feature is very experimental. It is known that several elements don't yet work in library mode. Careful testing is highly recommended._\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The lua interface allows you to use darktable from any lua script. This will load darktable as a library and provide you with most of the lua API (darktable is configured headless, so the functions relating to the user interface are not available).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As an example, the following program will print the list of all images in your library:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"#!/usr/bin/env lua\n"
"package = require \"package\"\n"
"package.cpath=package.cpath..\";./lib/darktable/lib?.so\"\n"
"\n"
"dt = require(\"darktable\")(\n"
"\"--library\", \"./library.db\",\n"
"\"--datadir\", \"./share/darktable\",\n"
"\"--moduledir\", \"./lib/darktable\",\n"
"\"--configdir\", \"./configdir\",\n"
"\"--cachedir\",\"cachedir\",\n"
"\"--g-fatal-warnings\")\n"
"\n"
"require(\"darktable.debug\")\n"
"\n"
"for k,v in ipairs(dt.database) do\n"
"   print(tostring(v))\n"
"end\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Note the third line that points to the location of the `libdarktable.so` file.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/darktable-from-lua.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Also note that the call to require returns a function that can be called only once and allows you to set darktable's command line parameter. The `:memory:` parameter to `--library` is useful here if you don't want to work on your personal library.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "exporting images with lua"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "So far we have learned to use lua to adapt darktable to our particular workflow. Let's look now at how to use lua to easily export images to an online service. If you are able to upload an image to a service via the command line then you can use lua to integrate this into darktable's user interface.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In this next example we will use lua to export via `scp`. A new storage type will appear in darktable's UI which will export images to a remote target via the copy mechanism in `ssh`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darktable = require \"darktable\"\n"
"\n"
"darktable.preferences.register(\"scp_export\",\"export_path\",\n"
"  \"string\",\"target SCP path\",\n"
"  \"Complete path to copy to. Can include user and hostname\",\"\")\n"
"\n"
"darktable.register_storage(\"scp_export\",\"Export via scp\",\n"
"  function( storage, image, format, filename,\n"
"     number, total, high_quality, extra_data)\n"
"    if not darktable.control.execute(\"scp \"..filename..\" \"..\n"
"      darktable.preferences.read(\"scp_export\",\n"
"         \"export_path\",\"string\")) then\n"
"      darktable.print_error(\"scp failed for \"..tostring(image))\n"
"    end\n"
"end)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "`darktable.preferences.register` will add a new preference to darktable's preferences menu, `scp_export` and `export_path` allow us to uniquely identify our preference. These fields are reused when we read the value of the preference. The `string` field tells the lua engine that the preference is a string. It could also be an integer, a filename or any of the types detailed in the API manual relating to `types_lua_pref_type` . We then have the label for the preference in the preference menu, the tooltip when hovering over the value and a default value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "`darktable.register_storage` is the call that actually registers a new storage type. The first argument is a name for the storage type, the second is the label that will be displayed in the UI and last is a function to call on each image. This function has a lot of parameters, but `filename` is the only one we use in this example. It contains the name of a temporary file where the image was exported by darktable's engine.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This code will work but it has a couple of limitations. This is just a simple example after all:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "We use preferences to configure the target path. It would be nicer to add an element to the export UI in darktable. We will detail how to do that in the next section\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "We do not check the returned value of `scp`. That command might fail, in particular if the user has not correctly set the preference.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "This script can't read input from the user. The remote `scp` must use password-less copy. `scp` can't be provided a password easily, so we will leave it that way\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "There is no message displayed once the example is done, only the progress bar on the lower left side tells the user that the job is done.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/lua/exporting-images.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "We use `coroutine.yield` to call an external program. The normal `os.execute` would block other lua codes from happening.\n"
msgstr ""

