#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "theory"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A wavelet is a mathematical function that starts off at zero, oscillates up and down and then settles back to zero. The following diagram shows some simple wavelets of differing sizes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-overview](./wavelets/wavelets-overview.png#w50) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "These wavelet functions are used to scan across and down the image using a mathematical operation called _convolution_. This picks out details from the image that are on a similar scale to the size of a given wavelet, and builds a number of detail layers each corresponding to a different wavelet scale.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Below is an example where detail layers have been extracted from the image shown above. In this case, the images were produced using the [_retouch_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md) module, splitting the image into 8 different layers, and using the module's controls to visualise the details present at each of these wavelet scales:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-retouch-gui](./wavelets/clean-retouch.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The bars in the _wavelet decompose_ section indicate the layers that have been extracted at different wavelet scales. The darkest rectangle at the left represents the entire image (before decomposition) and the gray boxes represent each of the decomposed layers. Clicking on the staircase icon below the bar graph enables the layer visualisation overlay so that you can see what the currently selected layer looks like. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Let's take a look at some of the layers generated for the above image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At scale #2, the image contains only very fine details, including the model's eyebrows, eye lashes and the pores of his skin. It doesn't include the coarser details of the image, because those details have been extracted to other layers:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-layer-scale-2](./wavelets/wavelets-layer-scale-2.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At scales #5 and #6 we begin to see larger and larger features:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-layer-scale-5](./wavelets/wavelets-layer-scale-5.png#w50) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-layer-scale-6](./wavelets/wavelets-layer-scale-6.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By scale #8 we only see very high-level features such as the overall shape of the model's nose, eye and the cheek:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-layer-scale-8](./wavelets/wavelets-layer-scale-8.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "why use wavelets?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Suppose, in the above example, that we wanted to smooth out some of the blotchiness in the model's skin, without losing any of the underlying skin texture. Wavelet decomposition makes this a trivial operation - we can simply use the retouch module to apply a Gaussian blur to only the 'blotchy' detail layer(s), leaving all other detail layers untouched. Once the adjustment is complete, the retouch module simply recombines that adjusted layer with the remaining untouched layers to produce the final image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The sequence of images below shows (1) The original image; (2) The layer (scale 5) that we wish to blur; and (3) The final image after the scale 5 layer has been blurred and the layers recombined:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-original](./wavelets/wavelets-original.png#w50) \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![wavelets-blur-layered](./wavelets/wavelets-blur-layered.png#w50)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As you can see, the large-scale skin blotches have been removed, but the smaller-scale details remain untouched.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "interacting with wavelet scales"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "There are two methods by which processing modules allow you to modify their operation using wavelet scales.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "wavelet decomposition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As discussed above, the _retouch_ module allows you to choose how many detail levels to split your image into. It decomposes the image into separate layers and allows you to perform operations selectively on each individual layer or on the image as a whole:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "See the [_retouch_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/retouch.md) module documentation for more details.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "spline controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [_denoise (profiled)_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/denoise-profiled.md), [_raw denoise_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/raw-denoise.md) and [_contrast equalizer_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/contrast-equalizer.md) modules allow their effects to be applied more or less to different wavelet scales using _splines_.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![spline](./wavelets/clean-spline.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Here, each node in the graph represents a different level of detail in the image, from coarse detail on the left to fine detail on the right. You can raise or lower each of these nodes with your mouse to increase or decrease the module's effect, respectively, on that wavelet scale. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/wavelets.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "To modify the curve, click slightly above or below the line near to a node and drag up or down. You can change the width of your modification by scrolling with your mouse wheel, which increases or reduces the size of the circle displayed under your mouse pointer. A small circle indicates that the effect of dragging the curve up or down will be isolated mostly to the node being adjusted. A larger circle indicates that the effect will be more broad and will increasingly impact adjacent nodes. When you hover your mouse over the graph, shaded areas indicate the parts of the spline that will be impacted when you attempt to modify the curve.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Sliders offer five different methods of interaction, depending on the level of control you require.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"left-click\n"
": Click anywhere in the slider area to set the value. You can also click and drag to change it. You don't have to aim for the triangle or even the line - you can click anywhere in the entire height of the slider including the label.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mouse wheel\n"
": Hover over the slider with your mouse, then use your mouse wheel to adjust the value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"keyboard arrow keys\n"
": When the slider has focus you can hover over the slider with your mouse, then use your keyboard's arrow keys (←/↓ and →/↑) to adjust the value. In order to give focus to the widget without changing the current value you can right-click, then right-click again.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"right-click\n"
": When your mouse is over a slider right-clicking enables a multi-functional pop-up below the slider for fine control with your mouse or numerical entry using the keyboard.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": ![bauhaus](./module-controls/bauhaus.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": A bent line extending from the triangular marker moves with your mouse. The closer your mouse pointer is to the triangular marker the coarser the control you have over the value; the further away from the triangular marker the finer your control. Left-click with your mouse to accept the new value and and hide the pop-up.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Alternatively you can type in a new value using your keyboard and commit by hitting the enter key. You may even supply the new value in the form of an arithmetic expression which darktable will calculate for you – the previous value is referenced as “x”.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"double-click\n"
": You can double-click on a slider or its label to reset to the default value.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In addition, the precision of mouse-wheel and arrow key-adjustments can be altered:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: ' - '
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "hold down the Shift key while adjusting to _increase_ the step size by a factor of 10. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: ' - '
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "hold down the Ctrl key while adjusting to _decrease_ the step size by a factor of 10.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Both of these multipliers can be amended in the `$HOME/.config/darktablerc` file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"darkroom/ui/scale_rough_step_multiplier=10.0\n"
"darkroom/ui/scale_precise_step_multiplier=0.1\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on a combobox to open a list of available options which you can click to select. Occasionally the selection list will open close to the bottom or top of the screen meaning that only some of the items are visible -- simply scroll with your mouse wheel to bring up the full list. Alternatively, you can also use the mouse wheel and keyboard arrow keys to select an option, or start typing to filter the combobox entries.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "A number of modules allow parameters to be set using color pickers (identified by the ![color-picker-icon](./module-controls/color-picker.png#icon) icon). These use a standard interface and most can operate in either point or area mode. Point mode can be activated by clicking on the color picker icon. Ctrl+click on the icon to activate area mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-controls.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Module parameters can also be amended with keyboard shortcuts. See [preferences > shortcuts](../../preferences-settings/shortcuts.md) for more information.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "curves"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Three processing modules ([base curve](../../module-reference/processing-modules/base-curve.md), [tone curve](../../module-reference/processing-modules/tone-curve.md) and [rgb curve](../../module-reference/processing-modules/rgb-curve.md)) use curves to control the tones in the image. These modules have some common features that deserve separate discussion.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![curve](./curves/curve.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "In their default state, curves are straight lines, defined by two anchor nodes at the top-right and bottom-left of the curve graph. You can move the nodes to modify the curve or generate new nodes by clicking on the curve. Ctrl+click to generate a new node at the x-location of the mouse pointer and the corresponding y-location of the current curve -- this adds a node without the risk of accidentally modifying the curve. Up to 20 nodes can be defined per curve. To remove a node, click on it and drag it out of the widget area.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "curve controls"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The following controls are common to two or more of the above processing modules and are therefore discussed separately here. Please see the individual module documentation for discussion of any additional module-specific controls.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"interpolation method \n"
": _tone curve and rgb curve modules only_\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Interpolation is the process by which a continuous curve is derived from a few nodes. As this process is never perfect, several methods are offered that can alleviate some of the issues you may encounter.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - Arguably, the most visually pleasing method is the “cubic spline” -- since it gives smooth curves, the contrast in the image is better enhanced. However, this method is very sensitive to the nodes' position, and can produce cusps and oscillations when the nodes are too close to each other, or when there are too many of them. This method works best when there are only 4 to 5 nodes, evenly spaced.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - The “centripetal spline” method is designed specifically to avoid cusps and oscillations, but as a drawback it will follow the nodes more loosely. It is very robust, no matter the number of nodes and their spacing, but will produce a more faded and dull contrast.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": - The “monotonic spline” method is designed specifically to give a monotonic interpolation, meaning that there will be none of the oscillations the cubic spline may produce. This method is most suitable when you are trying to build an analytical function from a node interpolation (for example: exponential, logarithm, power, etc.). Such functions are provided as presets. It is a good trade-off between the two aforementioned methods.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"preserve colors\n"
": If a non-linear tone curve is applied to each of the RGB channels individually, then the amount of tone adjustment applied to each color channel may be different, and this can cause hue shifts. Therefore, the _preserve colors_ combobox provides different methods of calculating the \"luminance level\" of a pixel. The amount of tone adjustment is calculated based on this luminance value, and then this same adjustment is applied to all three of the RGB channels. Different luminance estimators can affect the contrast in different parts of the image, depending on the specific characteristics of that image. The user can therefore choose a particular estimator that provides the best results for the given image. Some of these methods are discussed in detail in the **preserve chrominance** control in the [_filmic rgb_](../../module-reference/processing-modules/filmic-rgb.md) module. The following options are available:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
": - _none_\n"
": - _luminance_\n"
": - _max RGB_\n"
": - _average RGB_\n"
": - _sum RGB_\n"
": - _norm RGB_\n"
": - _basic power_\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"scale for graph \n"
": _tone curve and base curve modules only_\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": The scale allows you to distort the graph display so that certain graphical properties emerge to help you draw more useful curves. Note that the scaling option only affects the curve display, not the actual parameters stored by the module.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": By default, a “linear” scale is used (defined by a scale factor of 0). This scale uses evenly spaced abscissa and ordinates axes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": A logarithmic scale will compress the high values and dilate the low values, on both the abcissa and the axis of ordinates, so that the nodes in lowlights get more space on the graph and can be controlled more clearly.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/curves.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Increase the 'scale for graph' slider to set the base of the logarithm used to scale the axes. This allows you to control the amount of compression/dilation operated by the scale. If you draw purely exponential or logarithmic functions from identity lines, setting this value defines the base of such functions.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: YAML Front Matter: title
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, no-wrap
msgid "multiple instances"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Many of darktable's modules can be applied more than once in the pixelpipe. Each instance of a module behaves independently, taking its input from the module below in the pixelpipe delivering its output to the module above.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "As with the base instance of a module, all instances can be moved independently within the pixelpipe either by holding Ctrl+Shift while dragging & dropping or by choosing \"move up\" or \"move down\" in the _multiple instances_ drop-down menu.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Instances can be renamed by Ctrl+clicking on the module header.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "There are many occasions where it makes sense to have a module apply more than once in the pixelpipe. Here are some typical use cases.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: ' - '
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The [_exposure_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/exposure.md) module can be used in combination with [masks](../masking-and-blending/masks/_index.md) to lighten or darken parts of an image. A separate instance may be created to modify each part of the image.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '- '
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "You may wish to handle luma and chroma noise independently. This can be accomplished by generating two instances of your chosen denoising module and using the first one only on luma (by selecting [blend mode](../masking-and-blending/blend-modes.md) “lightness”) and the second one only on chroma (by selecting blend mode “color”).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Each instance also adds to the workload of your pixelpipe. Generating too many instances – especially of the more demanding modules – will cause noticeable slow-down.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title #
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "managing multiple instances"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the _multiple instance menu_ in the [module header](./module-header.md) to display a drop-down menu, with the following options. Right-click on the menu icon to create a new instance directly (same action as clicking on the \"new instance\" option of the menu).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"new instance\n"
": Create a new instance of the current module with all of its parameters reset to default. The 'instance name' is automatically set to a unique integer so that it can be distinguished from its parent.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"duplicate instance\n"
": Create a new instance of the current module with all of its parameters inherited from its parent. As with 'new instance' the 'instance name' is automatically set to a unique integer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"move up/down\n"
": Move the instance up or down in the pixelpipe\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"delete\n"
": Remove the current instance. This option is not available if only one instance is present.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/multiple-instances.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"rename\n"
": Rename the current instance. See the [history stack](../../../module-reference/utility-modules/lighttable/history-stack.md) section for more details on how the instance name impacts copying and pasting history stacks.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "At the top of each processing module is the _module header_. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "![module header](./module-header/module-header.png#w33)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "Click on the module name to expand the module and display the parameters that control its operation.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "By default darktable will only allow one processing module to be expanded at a time -- if you click the header of another module, the previously-opened module's controls are collapsed. If you want to expand more than one module, you may expand further modules by Shift+clicking on the header and all previously expanded modules will remain open. This behaviour can be reversed via a setting in [preferences > darkroom](../../../preferences-settings/darkroom.md).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "**Note:** Expanding a module does not cause it to be activated. See below for how to activate modules.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid "The module header contains the following controls in order from left to right:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ""
"on/off button\n"
": Click to toggle the module on or off. Some modules are essential for image processing and cannot be disabled (though their parameters may be amended). Similarly, some modules are not applicable for certain types of image and cannot be enabled.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
msgid ": Ctrl+click on the on/off button to toggle whether the module has focus. The focus state is usually used to activate any overlays that a module places over the image to control its functionality. For example, the [_crop & rotate_](../../../module-reference/processing-modules/crop-rotate.md) module only shows the composition and crop guide lines on the image if it has focus. \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: content/darkroom/processing-modules/module-header.md
#, markdown-text, no-wrap
